# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: atmosphere
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] In 2017, traces of water were discovered in the planet's atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] In 2019, the Nobel Prize in Physics was awarded in part for the discovery of 51 Pegasi b.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] 51 Pegasi is the Flamsteed designation of the host star.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] The planet was originally designated 51 Pegasi b by Michel Mayor and Didier Queloz, who discovered the planet in 1995.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] The following year it was unofficially dubbed "Bellerophon" /bɛˈlɛrəfɒn/ by astronomer Geoffrey Marcy, who followed the convention of naming planets after Greek and Roman mythological figures (Bellerophon is a figure from Greek mythology who rode the winged horse Pegasus).
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] In July 2014, the International Astronomical Union launched NameExoWorlds, a process for giving proper names to certain exoplanets and their host stars.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] The process involved public nomination and voting for the new names.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] In December 2015, the IAU announced the winning name for this planet was Dimidium.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] The name was submitted by the *Astronomische Gesellschaft Luzern* (German for 'Astronomical Society of Lucerne'), Switzerland.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] 'Dimidium' is Latin for 'half', referring to the planet's mass of approximately half the mass of Jupiter.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] The exoplanet's discovery was announced on October 6, 1995, by Michel Mayor and Didier Queloz of the University of Geneva in the journal *Nature*.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] They used the radial velocity method with the ELODIE spectrograph on the Observatoire de Haute-Provence telescope in France and made world headlines with their announcement.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] For this discovery, they were awarded the 2019 Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] The planet was discovered using a sensitive spectroscope that could detect the slight and regular velocity changes in the star's spectral lines of around 70 metres per second.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] These changes are caused by the planet's gravitational effects from just 7 million kilometres' distance from the star.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] Within a week of the announcement, the planet was confirmed by another team using the Lick Observatory in California.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] After its discovery, many teams confirmed the planet's existence and obtained more observations of its properties.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] It was discovered that the planet orbits the star in around four days.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] It is much closer to it than Mercury is to the Sun, moves at an orbital speed of 136 km/s (300,000 mph), yet has a minimum mass about half that of Jupiter (about 150 times that of the Earth).
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] At the time, the presence of a huge world so close to its star was not compatible with theories of planet formation and was considered an anomaly.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] However, since then, numerous other "hot Jupiters" have been discovered (such as those orbiting 55 Cancri and τ Boötis), and astronomers are revising their theories of planet formation to account for them by studying orbital migration.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] Assuming the planet is perfectly grey with no greenhouse or tidal effects, and a Bond albedo of 0.1, the temperature would be 1,265 K (992 °C; 1,817 °F).
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] In the report of the discovery, it was initially speculated that 51 Pegasi b was the stripped core of a brown dwarf of a decomposed star and was therefore composed of heavy elements, but it is now believed to be a gas giant.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] It is sufficiently massive that its thick atmosphere is not blown away by the star's solar wind.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] 51 Pegasi b probably has a greater radius than that of Jupiter despite its lower mass.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] This is because its superheated atmosphere must be puffed up into a thick but tenuous layer surrounding it.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] Beneath this, the gases that make up the planet would be so hot that the planet would glow red.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] Clouds of silicates may exist in the atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] The planet is tidally locked to its star, always presenting the same face to it.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] The planet (with Upsilon Andromedae b) was deemed a candidate for aperture polarimetry by Planetpol.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] It is also a candidate for "near-infrared characterisation... with the VLTI Spectro-Imager".
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] A 2015 study alleged the detection of 51 Pegasi b in the visible light spectrum using the High Accuracy Radial Velocity Planet Searcher (HARPS) instrument at the European Southern Observatory's La Silla Observatory in Chile.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] This detection, if confirmed, would allow the inference of a true mass of 0.46 Jupiter masses.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] The findings also could suggest a high albedo for the planet, hence a large radius up to 1.9±0.3 Jupiter radii, which could suggest 51 Pegasi b is an inflated hot Jupiter.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] The optical detection could not be replicated in 2021, implying the planet has an albedo below 0.15.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] Measurements in 2021 have marginally detected a polarized reflected light signal, which, while they cannot place limits on the albedo without assumptions made about the scattering mechanisms, could suggest a high albedo.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] A 2022 study found no evidence of reflected light, ruling out the previous radii and albedo estimates from previous studies.
[src:atmosphere/51-pegasi-b] Instead, 51 Pegasi b is likely a low-albedo planet with a radius around 1.2±0.1 *R*J.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] In 2026, astronomers announced the discovery of a thin atmosphere around 2002 XV93, making it likely the first TNO after Pluto discovered to have an atmosphere, and defying expectations that it should be too small to hold onto an atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] With a surface pressure of 100–200 nanobars (roughly 5 million to 10 million times thinner than Earth's atmosphere or 50 to 100 times thinner than Pluto's atmosphere), it is predicted that 2002 XV93 should lose all of its atmosphere in 100 to 1,000 years.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] The existence of 2002 XV93's atmosphere suggests it was recently replenished, either by a comet impact or outgassing via cryovolcanic eruptions.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] The composition of the atmosphere is unknown, but it is thought to contain either nitrogen, argon, or methane.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] 2002 XV93 was discovered on 10 December 2002 (Universal Time; UT) by Palomar Observatory in California, United States.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] At that time, a team of astronomers led by Chad Trujillo and Michael E.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Brown were working in Palomar Observatory using its 1.2-m Samuel Oschin telescope, operating jointly with the Near-Earth Asteroid Tracking (NEAT) program.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] The object's discovery was announced by the Minor Planet Center (MPC) on 5 January 2003.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Precovery observations of 2002 XV93 from Palomar Observatory were later identified in 2008, with the observations dating to 16 October 1990, 12 October 1991, and 28 September 1992.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] On 10 January 2024 (UT), 2002 XV93 passed in front of a magnitude-15.8 star in the constellation Auriga, causing it to briefly dim from Earth for up to 20 seconds.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] This event, known as a stellar occultation, was predicted and observed in Japan by a team of astronomers led by Ko Arimatsu of the National Astronomical Observatory of Japan.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Telescopes were stationed at Kyoto University, Kiso Observatory, Fukushima Prefecture, and Okayama Observatory, but only the first three sites detected the occultation.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] All detections showed that the star faded gradually (lasting up to 1.5 seconds) rather than abruptly during the occultation, revealing that 2002 XV93 had an atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] The discovery was announced on 4 May 2026, making 2002 XV93 likely the first trans-Neptunian object after Pluto discovered to have an atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] This object is currently known by its minor planet provisional designation 2002 XV93, given by the MPC upon its discovery.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] The MPC gave it the minor planet number of 612533 on 28 March 2022.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] According to naming guidelines by the International Astronomical Union's Working Group for Small Bodies Nomenclature, trans-Neptunian objects classified as plutinos, such as 2002 XV93, should be given mythological names related to the underworld.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Since 2002 XV93 received its minor planet number less than 10 years ago, only the discoverer has the privilege of naming it.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] In an interview with *Reuters* on 4 May 2026, Arimatsu remarked that the current designation of 2002 XV93 is unmemorable and advocated for a name related to Okinawan mythology, such as Amamikyu (/əˈmɑːmikjuː/).
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Brown, who was involved in Palomar Observatory's discovery of 2002 XV93, commented that the object did not get named because it had no known remarkable properties before Arimatsu's discovery of its atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] 2002 XV93 orbits the Sun's barycenter with a semi-major axis of 39.3 astronomical units (AU), putting it in the Kuiper belt beyond Neptune's orbit.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] 2002 XV93 takes 246 years to complete one orbit, which places it in a 2:3 mean-motion resonance with Neptune.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] For every two revolutions it makes around the Sun, Neptune makes exactly three.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] It is therefore a member of the plutinos, a large population of trans-Neptunian objects (TNOs) named after its largest member Pluto.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] 2002 XV93's orbit is elliptical, with an orbital eccentricity of 0.12, and inclined by 13° with respect to the ecliptic.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Its distance from the Sun ranges from 34.4 AU at perihelion to 44.2 AU at aphelion.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] 2002 XV93 will come to perihelion in March 2070.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Due to gravitational perturbations by the giant planets, the orbital elements of 2002 XV93 vary over time.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Simulations of 2002 XV93's orbit show that in 10 million years, its semi-major axis can fluctuate between 39.1–39.9 AU, eccentricity between 0.10–0.15, and inclination between 12.5–13.9°.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Observations of a stellar occultation in 2024 show that 2002 XV93 has a radius of 235+22 −15 km, or a diameter of 470+44 −30 km, assuming it has a spherical shape.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] For comparison, 2002 XV93 is about one-seventh the diameter of Earth's moon and about one-fifth the diameter of Pluto.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] The mass, bulk density, and shape of 2002 XV93 are unknown, though they can be inferred from those of other similarly-sized TNOs like Huya.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] A 2026 study by Arimatsu and colleagues assumed 2002 XV93 had a bulk density between 1.0 and 1.5 g/cm3, similar to those of Huya and Pluto's moon Charon, respectively.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] The surface gravity of 2002 XV93 is estimated to be around 100 times weaker than Earth's.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Arimatsu and colleagues expect that 2002 XV93 has a non-spherical shape due to its relatively small diameter of a few hundred kilometres.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] The rotation period of 2002 XV93 is unknown and it has not yet been studied via light curves, according to the *Asteroid Lightcurve Database*.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Some astronomers, including Noemi Pinilla-Alonso and Michael E.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Brown, previously suggested that 2002 XV93 could be theoretically large enough to become spherical and be possibly a dwarf planet, based on a larger diameter estimate from 2012.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] This outdated estimate had 2002 XV93 549.2+21.7 −23.0 km in diameter, based on mid- to far-infrared measurements of its thermal emission by the Herschel Space Observatory and Spitzer Space Telescope.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Measurements of 2002 XV93's visible brightness and infrared thermal radiation suggest that its surface is dark, with a very low geometric albedo of 0.040+0.020 −0.015.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] However, this estimate was made in 2012 using a visible-light (V-band) absolute magnitude 5.42±0.46 and thermal emission-derived diameter of 549.2+21.7 −23.0 km.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] More recent measurements have since found a brighter V-band absolute magnitude of 4.73 and a smaller diameter of 470+44 −30 km, which should indicate a higher albedo for 2002 XV93.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] However, as of May 2026, no peer-reviewed studies have recalculated 2002 XV93's albedo using newer measurements of its absolute magnitude and diameter.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Telescopic observations in visible light show that the surface color of 2002 XV93 is gray, similar to some centaurs and Kuiper belt objects including Achlys and 2004 EW95.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Due to 2002 XV93's great distance from the Sun, its surface temperature averages around 47 K (−226.2 °C; −375.1 °F), cold enough to freeze substances like water into solid ice.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Near-infrared spectroscopy by the James Webb Space Telescope (JWST) has shown that the surface of 2002 XV93 is rich in water ice, in both amorphous and crystalline phases.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] The abundance of water ice in 2002 XV93's surface is indicated by the presence of absorption bands at wavelengths of 1.5, 2.0, 3.0, and 4.5 μm in the object's near-infrared spectrum, alongside a reflectance peak at 3.1 μm due to crystalline water ice.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] In the Kuiper belt, crystalline water ice tends to transform into amorphous water ice due to irradiation by cosmic rays, though both phases are expected to be in equilibrium (i.e. amounts of crystalline and amorphous water ice remain constant).
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] 2002 XV93 shares its water ice-rich surface composition with other TNOs, including the plutinos 2004 EW95 and 2003 UZ413.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] These TNOs are classified as "prominent water"-type or "Bowl"-type TNOs, because their near-infrared spectra display a significant bowl-shaped water ice absorption band at the wavelength of 3.0 μm.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Besides water, JWST has detected frozen carbon dioxide (CO 2) on 2002 XV93's surface.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] JWST has also detected trace amounts of 13CO 2 (a rare isotopologue of CO 2).
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] In observations from 2022 and 2024, JWST found no signs of hypervolatile compounds such as methane, nitrogen, and carbon monoxide (which can sublimate into gases at 2002 XV93's temperature).
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] The lack of hypervolatiles on 2002 XV93's surface suggests that most of them had already sublimated and escaped into space.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] In May 2026, a research team led by Ko Arimatsu announced the discovery of a thin atmosphere around 2002 XV93, making it possibly the first TNO after Pluto discovered to have an atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] The atmosphere was inferred from observations of a stellar occultation in January 2024, when 2002 XV93 passed in front of a star and dimmed its light gradually (lasting 1.5 seconds) instead of abruptly, indicating refraction by an atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] The gradual disappearance and reappearance of the star was observed to occur within radii of 230 to 270 km (140 to 170 mi) from 2002 XV93's center.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Alternate explanations for this gradual fading, such as a ring system or a shell of dust, are considered unlikely.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] At this pressure, 2002 XV93's atmosphere is dense enough (>0.001 nanobar) that its gas molecules can collide amongst themselves, making it a true atmosphere rather than an exosphere.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] No other TNO besides Pluto is known to have an atmospheric pressure this high.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] However, it is unclear how the density of 2002 XV93's atmosphere changes with altitude.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] The composition 2002 XV93's atmosphere is unknown, and there are competing hypotheses for it.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] One possible composition is methane, a common hypervolatile found in TNOs.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] In occultation observations, 2002 XV93's atmosphere appeared to show a sudden change in refraction at a certain altitude, suggesting that it has a thermal inversion caused by upper-atmospheric heating of trace methane gas (similar to Pluto).
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] However, JWST observed the object after its 2024 occultation and found no signs of methane and carbon monoxide gas, suggesting they do not make up much of its atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] If these gases exist over a large altitude range, their partial pressures at 2002 XV93's surface must be less than 0.0003 nanobars (0.3 picobars).
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] However, it remains possible that a low-altitude atmosphere of pure methane could exist.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Using these JWST observations, a research team headed by Ian Wong proposed that 2002 XV93's atmosphere could contain either nitrogen, argon, or any other gas that couldn't be detected by JWST.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] The discovery of an atmosphere around 2002 XV93 was unexpected because the object is too small to have a surface gravity strong enough to theoretically hold on to an atmosphere over the age of the Solar System.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Physical models predict that 2002 XV93 should lose all of its atmosphere within 100 to 1,000 years via Jeans escape.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] The present-day existence of 2002 XV93's atmosphere implies that it was recently replenished, though the cause is unknown.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Sublimation of volatile ices on 2002 XV93's surface is unlikely, because it was not detected in earlier JWST observations.
[src:atmosphere/612533-2002-xv93] Arimatsu's team hypothesized that 2002 XV93 obtained its atmosphere via either an impact by a hundred-meter-radius comet, or outgassing by cryovolcanic eruptions.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] In astrophysics, **accretion** is the accumulation of particles into a massive object by gravitationally attracting more matter, typically gaseous matter, into an accretion disk.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Most astronomical objects, such as galaxies, stars, and planets, are formed by accretion processes.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The accretion model that Earth and the other terrestrial planets formed from meteoric material was proposed in 1944 by Otto Schmidt, followed by the *protoplanet theory* of William McCrea (1960) and finally the *capture theory* of Michael Woolfson.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] In 1978, Andrew Prentice resurrected the initial Laplacian ideas about planet formation and developed the *modern Laplacian theory*.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] None of these models proved completely successful, and many of the proposed theories were descriptive.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The 1944 accretion model by Otto Schmidt was further developed in a quantitative way in 1969 by Viktor Safronov.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] He calculated, in detail, the different stages of terrestrial planet formation.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Since then, the model has been further developed using intensive numerical simulations to study planetesimal accumulation.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] It is now accepted that stars form by the gravitational collapse of interstellar gas.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Prior to collapse, this gas is mostly in the form of molecular clouds, such as the Orion Nebula.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] As the cloud collapses, losing potential energy, it heats up, gaining kinetic energy, and the conservation of angular momentum ensures that the cloud forms a flattened disk—the accretion disk.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] A few hundred thousand years after the Big Bang, the Universe cooled to the point where atoms could form.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] As the Universe continued to expand and cool, the atoms lost enough kinetic energy, and dark matter coalesced sufficiently, to form protogalaxies.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] As further accretion occurred, galaxies formed.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Galaxies grow through mergers and smooth gas accretion.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Accretion also occurs inside galaxies, forming stars.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Stars are thought to form inside giant clouds of cold molecular hydrogen — giant molecular clouds of roughly 300,000 *M*☉ and 65 light-years (20 pc) in diameter.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Over millions of years, giant molecular clouds are prone to collapse and fragmentation.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] These fragments then form small, dense cores, which in turn collapse into stars.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The cores range in mass from a fraction to several times that of the Sun and are called protostellar (protosolar) nebulae.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Compare it with the particle number density of the air at the sea level — 2.8×1019/cm3 (4.6×1020/cu in).
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The initial collapse of a solar-mass protostellar nebula takes around 100,000 years.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Every nebula begins with a certain amount of angular momentum.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Gas in the central part of the nebula, with relatively low angular momentum, undergoes fast compression and forms a hot hydrostatic (non-contracting) core containing a small fraction of the mass of the original nebula.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] This core forms the seed of what will become a star.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] As the collapse continues, conservation of angular momentum dictates that the rotation of the infalling envelope accelerates, which eventually forms a disk.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] As the infall of material from the disk continues, the envelope eventually becomes thin and transparent and the young stellar object (YSO) becomes observable, initially in far-infrared light and later in the visible.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Around this time the protostar begins to fuse deuterium.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] If the protostar is sufficiently massive (above 80 *M*J), hydrogen fusion follows.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Otherwise, if its mass is too low, the object becomes a brown dwarf.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] This birth of a new star occurs approximately 100,000 years after the collapse begins.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Objects at this stage are known as Class I protostars, which are also called young T Tauri stars, evolved protostars, or young stellar objects.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] By this time, the forming star has already accreted much of its mass; the total mass of the disk and remaining envelope does not exceed 10–20% of the mass of the central YSO.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] At the next stage, the envelope completely disappears, having been gathered up by the disk, and the protostar becomes a classical T Tauri star.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The latter have accretion disks and continue to accrete hot gas, which manifests itself by strong emission lines in their spectrum.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The former do not possess accretion disks.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Classical T Tauri stars evolve into weakly lined T Tauri stars.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] This happens after about 1 million years.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The mass of the disk around a classical T Tauri star is about 1–3% of the stellar mass, and it is accreted at a rate of 10−7 to 10−9 *M*☉ per year.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] A pair of bipolar jets is usually present as well.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The accretion explains all peculiar properties of classical T Tauri stars: strong flux in the emission lines (up to 100% of the intrinsic luminosity of the star), magnetic activity, photometric variability and jets.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The emission lines actually form as the accreted gas hits the "surface" of the star, which happens around its magnetic poles.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The jets are byproducts of accretion: they carry away excessive angular momentum.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The classical T Tauri stage lasts about 10 million years (there are only a few examples of so-called Peter Pan disks, where the accretion continues to persist for much longer periods, sometimes lasting for more than 40 million years).
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The disk eventually disappears due to accretion onto the central star, planet formation, ejection by jets, and photoevaporation by ultraviolet radiation from the central star and nearby stars.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] As a result, the young star becomes a weakly lined T Tauri star, which, over hundreds of millions of years, evolves into an ordinary Sun-like star, dependent on its initial mass.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Self-accretion of cosmic dust accelerates the growth of the particles into boulder-sized planetesimals.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The more massive planetesimals accrete some smaller ones, while others shatter in collisions.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Accretion disks are common around smaller stars, stellar remnants in a close binary, or black holes surrounded by material (such as those at the centers of galaxies).
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Some dynamics in the disk, such as dynamical friction, are necessary to allow orbiting gas to lose angular momentum and fall onto the central massive object.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Occasionally, this can result in stellar surface fusion (see Bondi accretion).
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] In the formation of terrestrial planets or planetary cores, several stages can be considered.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] First, when gas and dust grains collide, they agglomerate by microphysical processes like van der Waals forces and electromagnetic forces, forming micrometer-sized particles.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] During this stage, accumulation mechanisms are largely non-gravitational in nature.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] However, planetesimal formation in the centimeter-to-meter range is not well understood, and no convincing explanation is offered as to why such grains would accumulate rather than simply rebound.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Ward (1996) suggests that when slow moving grains collide, the very low, yet non-zero, gravity of colliding grains impedes their escape.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] It is also thought that grain fragmentation plays an important role replenishing small grains and keeping the disk thick, but also in maintaining a relatively high abundance of solids of all sizes.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] A number of mechanisms have been proposed for crossing the 'meter-sized' barrier.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Local concentrations of pebbles may form, which then gravitationally collapse into planetesimals the size of large asteroids.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] These concentrations can occur passively due to the structure of the gas disk, for example, between eddies, at pressure bumps, at the edge of a gap created by a giant planet, or at the boundaries of turbulent regions of the disk.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Or, the particles may take an active role in their concentration via a feedback mechanism referred to as a streaming instability.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] In a streaming instability the interaction between the solids and the gas in the protoplanetary disk results in the growth of local concentrations, as new particles accumulate in the wake of small concentrations, causing them to grow into massive filaments.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Alternatively, if the grains that form due to the agglomeration of dust are highly porous their growth may continue until they become large enough to collapse due to their own gravity.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The low density of these objects allows them to remain strongly coupled with the gas, thereby avoiding high velocity collisions which could result in their erosion or fragmentation.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Grains eventually stick together to form mountain-size (or larger) bodies called planetesimals.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Collisions and gravitational interactions between planetesimals combine to produce Moon-size planetary embryos (protoplanets) over roughly 0.1–1 million years.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Finally, the planetary embryos collide to form planets over 10–100 million years.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The planetesimals are massive enough that mutual gravitational interactions are significant enough to be taken into account when computing their evolution.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Growth is aided by orbital decay of smaller bodies due to gas drag, which prevents them from being stranded between orbits of the embryos.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Further collisions and accumulation lead to terrestrial planets or the core of giant planets.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] If the planetesimals formed via the gravitational collapse of local concentrations of pebbles, their growth into planetary embryos and the cores of giant planets is dominated by the further accretions of pebbles.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Pebble accretion is aided by the gas drag felt by objects as they accelerate toward a massive body.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Gas drag slows the pebbles below the escape velocity of the massive body causing them to spiral toward and to be accreted by it.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Pebble accretion may accelerate the formation of planets by a factor of 1000 compared to the accretion of planetesimals, allowing giant planets to form before the dissipation of the gas disk.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] However, core growth via pebble accretion appears incompatible with the final masses and compositions of Uranus and Neptune.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Direct calculations indicate that, in a typical protoplanetary disk, the formation time of a giant planet via pebble accretion is comparable to the formation times resulting from planetesimal accretion.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The formation of terrestrial planets differs from that of giant gas planets, also called Jovian planets.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The particles that make up the terrestrial planets are made from metal and rock that condensed in the inner Solar System.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] However, Jovian planets began as large, icy planetesimals, which then captured hydrogen and helium gas from the solar nebula.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Differentiation between these two classes of planetesimals arises due to the frost line of the solar nebula.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Meteorites contain a record of accretion and impacts during all stages of asteroid origin and evolution; however, the mechanism of asteroid accretion and growth is not well understood.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Evidence suggests the main growth of asteroids can result from gas-assisted accretion of chondrules, which are millimeter-sized spherules that form as molten (or partially molten) droplets in space before being accreted to their parent asteroids.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] In the inner Solar System, chondrules appear to have been crucial for initiating accretion.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The tiny mass of asteroids may be partly due to inefficient chondrule formation beyond 2 AU, or less-efficient delivery of chondrules from near the protostar.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Also, impacts controlled the formation and destruction of asteroids, and are thought to be a major factor in their geological evolution.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Chondrules, metal grains, and other components likely formed in the solar nebula.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] These accreted together to form parent asteroids.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Some of these bodies subsequently melted, forming metallic cores and olivine-rich mantles; others were aqueously altered.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] After the asteroids had cooled, they were eroded by impacts for 4.5 billion years, or disrupted.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] For accretion to occur, impact velocities must be less than about twice the escape velocity, which is about 140 m/s (460 ft/s) for a 100 km (60 mi) radius asteroid.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Simple models for accretion in the asteroid belt generally assume micrometer-sized dust grains sticking together and settling to the midplane of the nebula to form a dense layer of dust, which, because of gravitational forces, was converted into a disk of kilometer-sized planetesimals.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] But, several arguments suggest that asteroids may not have accreted this way.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Comets, or their precursors, formed in the outer Solar System, possibly millions of years before planet formation.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] How and when comets formed is debated, with distinct implications for Solar System formation, dynamics, and geology.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Three-dimensional computer simulations indicate the major structural features observed on cometary nuclei can be explained by pairwise low velocity accretion of weak cometesimals.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The currently favored formation mechanism is that of the nebular hypothesis, which states that comets are probably a remnant of the original planetesimal "building blocks" from which the planets grew.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Astronomers think that comets originate in both the Oort cloud and the scattered disk.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Because the scattered disk is dynamically active and the Kuiper belt relatively dynamically stable, the scattered disk is now seen as the most likely point of origin for periodic comets.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The classic Oort cloud theory states that the Oort cloud, a sphere measuring about 50,000 AU (0.24 pc) in radius, formed at the same time as the solar nebula and occasionally releases comets into the inner Solar System as a giant planet or star passes nearby and causes gravitational disruptions.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Examples of such comet clouds may already have been seen in the Helix Nebula.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] The *Rosetta* mission to comet 67P/Churyumov–Gerasimenko determined in 2015 that when Sun's heat penetrates the surface, it triggers evaporation (sublimation) of buried ice.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] While some of the resulting water vapour may escape from the nucleus, 80% of it recondenses in layers beneath the surface.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] This observation implies that the thin ice-rich layers exposed close to the surface may be a consequence of cometary activity and evolution, and that global layering does not necessarily occur early in the comet's formation history.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] While most scientists thought that all the evidence indicated that the structure of nuclei of comets is processed rubble piles of smaller ice planetesimals of a previous generation, the *Rosetta* mission confirmed the idea that comets are "rubble piles" of disparate material.
[src:atmosphere/accretion-astrophysics] Comets appear to have formed as ~100-km bodies, then overwhelmingly ground/recontacted into their present states.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The term is derived from the name of the Greek god Aeolus, the keeper of the winds.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Aeolian processes are most important in areas where there is little or no vegetation.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] However, aeolian deposits are not restricted to arid climates.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] They are also seen along shorelines; along stream courses in semiarid climates; in areas of ample sand weathered from weakly cemented sandstone outcrops; and in areas of glacial outwash.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Loess, which is silt deposited by wind, is common in humid to subhumid climates.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Much of North America and Europe are underlain by sand and loess of Pleistocene age originating from glacial outwash.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The lee (downwind) side of river valleys in semiarid regions are often blanketed with sand and sand dunes.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Examples in North America include the Platte, Arkansas, and Missouri Rivers.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Wind erodes the Earth's surface by *deflation* (the removal of loose, fine-grained particles by the turbulent action of the wind) and by *abrasion* (the wearing down of surfaces by the grinding action and sandblasting by windborne particles).
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Once entrained in the wind, collisions between particles further break them down, a process called *attrition*.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Worldwide, erosion by water is more important than erosion by wind, but wind erosion is important in semiarid and arid regions.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Wind erosion is increased by some human activities, such as the use of 4x4 vehicles.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Deflation is the lifting and removal of loose material from the surface by wind turbulence.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] It takes place by three mechanisms: traction/surface creep, saltation, and suspension.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Traction or surface creep is a process of larger grains sliding or rolling across the surface.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Saltation refers to particles bouncing across the surface for short distances.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Suspended particles are fully entrained in the wind, which carries them for long distances.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Saltation likely accounts for 50–70 % of deflation, while suspension accounts for 30–40 % and surface creep accounts for 5–25 %.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Regions which experience intense and sustained erosion are called deflation zones.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Most aeolian deflation zones are composed of desert pavement, a sheet-like surface of rock fragments that remains after wind and water have removed the fine particles.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The rock mantle in desert pavements protects the underlying material from further deflation.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Areas of desert pavement form the *regs* or stony deserts of the Sahara.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] These are further divided into rocky areas called *hamadas* and areas of small rocks and gravel called *serirs*.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Desert pavement is extremely common in desert environments.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Blowouts are hollows formed by wind deflation.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Blowouts are generally small, but may be up to several kilometers in diameter.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The smallest are mere dimples 0.3 meters (1 ft) deep and 3 meters (10 ft) in diameter.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The largest include the blowout hollows of Mongolia, which can be 8 kilometers (5 mi) across and 60 to 100 meters (200 to 400 ft) deep.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Big Hollow in Wyoming, US, extends 14 by 9.7 kilometers (9 by 6 mi) and is up to 90 meters (300 ft) deep.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Abrasion (also sometimes called *corrasion*) is the process of wind-driven grains knocking or wearing material off of landforms.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] It was once considered a major contributor to desert erosion, but by the mid-20th Century, it had come to be considered much less important.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Wind can normally lift sand only a short distance, with most windborne sand remaining within 50 centimeters (20 in) of the surface and practically none normally being carried above 2 meters (6 ft).
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Many desert features once attributed to wind abrasion, including wind caves, mushroom rocks, and the honeycomb weathering called tafoni, are now attributed to differential weathering, rainwash, deflation rather than abrasion, or other processes.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Abrasion produces polishing and pitting, grooving, shaping, and faceting of exposed surfaces.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] These are widespread in arid environments but geologically insignificant.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Polished or faceted surfaces called *ventifacts* are rare, requiring abundant sand, powerful winds, and a lack of vegetation for their formation.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] In parts of Antarctica wind-blown snowflakes that are technically sediments have also caused abrasion of exposed rocks.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Attrition is the wearing down by collisions of particles entrained in a moving fluid.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] It is effective at rounding sand grains and at giving them a distinctive *frosted* surface texture.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Collisions between windborne particles is a major source of dust in the size range of 2-5 microns.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Most of this is produced by the removal of a weathered clay coating from the grains.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Wind dominates the transport of sand and finer sediments in arid environments.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Wind transport is also important in periglacial areas, on river flood plains, and in coastal areas.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Coastal winds transport significant amounts of siliciclastic and carbonate sediments inland, while wind storms and dust storms can carry clay and silt particles great distances.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Wind transports much of the sediments deposited in deep ocean basins.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] In *ergs* (desert sand seas), wind is very effective at transporting grains of sand size and smaller.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Particles are transported by winds through suspension, saltation (skipping or bouncing) and creeping (rolling or sliding) along the ground.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The minimum wind velocity to initiate transport is called the *fluid threshold* or *static threshold* and is the wind velocity required to begin dislodging grains from the surface.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Once transport is initiated, there is a cascade effect from grains tearing loose other grains, so that transport continues until the wind velocity drops below the *dynamic threshold* or *impact threshold*, which is usually less than the fluid threshold.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] In other words, there is hysteresis in the wind transport system.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Small particles may be held in the atmosphere in suspension.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Turbulent air motion supports the weight of suspended particles and allows them to be transported for great distances.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Wind is particularly effective at separating sediment grains under 0.05 mm in size from coarser grains as suspended particles.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Saltation is downwind movement of particles in a series of jumps or skips.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Saltation is most important for grains of up to 2 mm in size.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] A saltating grain may hit other grains that jump up to continue the saltation.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The grain may also hit larger grains (over 2 mm in size) that are too heavy to hop, but that slowly creep forward as they are pushed by saltating grains.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Surface creep accounts for as much as 25 percent of grain movement in a desert.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Vegetation is effective at suppressing aeolian transport.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Vegetation cover of as little as 15% is sufficient to eliminate most sand transport.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The size of shore dunes is limited mostly by the amount of open space between vegetated areas.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Aeolian transport from deserts plays an important role in ecosystems globally.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] For example, wind transports minerals from the Sahara to the Amazon basin.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Saharan dust is also responsible for forming red clay soils in southern Europe.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Dust storms are wind storms that have entrained enough dust to reduce visibility to less than 1 kilometer (0.6 mi).
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Most occur on the synoptic (regional) scale, due to strong winds along weather fronts, or locally from downbursts from thunderstorms.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Crops, people, and possibly even climates are affected by dust storms.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] On Earth, dust can cross entire oceans, as occurs with dust from the Sahara that reaches the Amazon Basin.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Dust storms on Mars periodically engulf the entire planet.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] When the Mariner 9 spacecraft entered its orbit around Mars in 1971, a dust storm lasting one month covered the entire planet, thus delaying the task of photo-mapping the planet's surface.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Most of the dust carried by dust storms is in the form of silt-size particles.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Deposits of this windblown silt are known as loess.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The thickest known deposit of loess, up to 350 meters (1,150 ft), is on the Loess Plateau in China.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] This very same Asian dust is blown for thousands of miles, forming deep beds in places as far away as Hawaii.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The Peoria Loess of North America is up to 40 meters (130 ft) thick in parts of western Iowa.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The soils developed on loess are generally highly productive for agriculture.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Small whirlwinds, called dust devils, are common in arid lands and are thought to be related to very intense local heating of the air that results in instabilities of the air mass.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Dust devils may be as much as one kilometer high.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Dust devils on Mars have been observed as high as 10 kilometers (6.2 mi), though this is uncommon.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Wind is very effective at separating sand from silt and clay.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] As a result, there are distinct sandy (erg) and silty (loess) aeolian deposits, with only limited interbedding between the two.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Loess deposits are found further from the original source of sediments than ergs.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] An example of this is the Sand Hills of Nebraska, US.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Here vegetation-stabilized sand dunes are found to the west and loess deposits to the east, further from the original sediment source in the Ogallala Formation at the feet of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Some of the most significant experimental measurements on aeolian landforms were performed by Ralph Alger Bagnold, a British army engineer who worked in Egypt prior to World War II.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Bagnold investigated the physics of particles moving through the atmosphere and deposited by wind.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] He recognized two basic dune types, the crescentic dune, which he called "barchan", and the linear dune, which he called longitudinal or "seif" (Arabic for "sword").
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Bagnold developed a classification scheme that included small-scale ripples and sand sheets as well as various types of dunes.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Bagnold's classification is most applicable in areas devoid of vegetation.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] In 1941, John Tilton Hack added parabolic dunes, which are strongly influenced by vegetation, to the list of dune types.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The discovery of dunes on Mars reinvigorated aeolian process research, which increasingly makes use of computer simulation.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Wind-deposited materials hold clues to past as well as to present wind directions and intensities.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] These features help us understand the present climate and the forces that molded it.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] For example, vast inactive ergs in much of the modern world attest to late Pleistocene trade wind belts being much expanded during the Last Glacial Maximum.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Ice cores show a tenfold increase in non-volcanic dust during glacial maxima.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The highest dust peak in the Vostok ice cores dates to 20 to 21 thousand years ago.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The abundant dust is attributed to a vigorous low-latitude wind system plus more exposed continental shelf due to low sea levels.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Wind-deposited sand bodies occur as ripples and other small-scale features, sand sheets, and dunes.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Wind blowing on a sand surface ripples the surface into crests and troughs whose long axes are perpendicular to the wind direction.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The average length of jumps during saltation corresponds to the wavelength, or distance between adjacent crests, of the ripples.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] In ripples, the coarsest materials collect at the crests causing inverse grading.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] This distinguishes small ripples from dunes, where the coarsest materials are generally in the troughs.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] This is also a distinguishing feature between water laid ripples and aeolian ripples.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] A *sand shadow* is an accumulation of sand on the downwind side of an obstruction, such as a boulder or an isolated patch of vegetation.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Here the sand builds up to the angle of repose (the maximum stable slope angle), about 34 degrees, then begins sliding down the *slip face* of the patch.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] A *sandfall* is a sand shadow of a cliff or escarpment.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Closely related to sand shadows are *sand drifts*.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] These form downwind of a gap between obstructions, due to the funneling effect of the obstructions on the wind.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Sand sheets are flat or gently undulating sandy deposits with only small surface ripples.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] An example is the Selima Sand Sheet in the eastern Sahara Desert, which occupies 60,000 square kilometers (23,000 sq mi) in southern Egypt and northern Sudan.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] This consists of a few feet of sand resting on bedrock.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Sand sheets are often remarkably flat and are sometimes described as *desert peneplains*.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Sand sheets are common in desert environments, particularly on the margins of dune fields, although they also occur within ergs.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Conditions that favor the formation of sand sheets, instead of dunes, may include surface cementation, a high water table, the effects of vegetation, periodic flooding, or sediments rich in grains too coarse for effective saltation.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] A dune is an accumulations of sediment blown by the wind into a mound or ridge.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] They differ from sand shadows or sand drifts in that they are independent of any topographic obstacle.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Dunes have gentle upwind slopes on the windward side.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The downwind portion of the dune, the lee slope, is commonly a steep avalanche slope referred to as a slipface.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The minimum height of a slipface is about 30 centimeters.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Wind-blown sand moves up the gentle upwind side of the dune by saltation or creep.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Sand accumulates at the brink, the top of the slipface.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] When the buildup of sand at the brink exceeds the angle of repose, a small avalanche of grains slides down the slipface.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Grain by grain, the dune moves downwind.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Linear dunes, also called longitudinal dunes or seifs, are aligned in the direction of the prevailing winds.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Transverse dunes, which include crescent dunes (barchans), are aligned perpendicular to the prevailing winds.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] More complex dunes, such as star dunes, form where the directions of the winds are highly variable.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Additional dune types arise from various kinds of topographic forcing, such as from isolated hills or escarpments.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Transverse dunes occur in areas dominated by a single direction of the prevailing wind.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] In areas where sand is not abundant, transverse dunes take the form of barchans or crescent dunes.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] These are not common, but they are highly recognizable, with a distinctive crescent shape with the tips of the crescent directed downwind.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The dunes are widely separated by areas of bedrock or reg.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Barchans migrate up to 30 meters (98 ft) per year, with the taller dunes migrating faster.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Barchans first form when some minor topographic feature creates a sand patch.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] This grows into a sand mound, and the converging streamlines of the air flow around the mound build it into the distinctive crescent shape.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Growth is ultimately limited by the carrying capacity of the wind, which as the wind becomes saturated with sediments, builds up the slip face of the dune.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Because barchans develop in areas of limited sand availability, they are poorly preserved in the geologic record.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Where sand is more abundant, transverse dunes take the form of aklé dunes, such as those of the western Sahara.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] These form a network of sinuous ridges perpendicular to the wind direction.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Aklé dunes are preserved in the geologic record as sandstone with large sets of cross-bedding and many reactivation surfaces.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Draas are very large composite transverse dunes.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] They can be up to 4,000 meters (13,000 ft) across and 400 meters (1,300 ft) high and extend lengthwise for hundreds of kilometers.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] In form, they resemble a large aklé or barchanoid dune.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] They form over a prolonged period of time in areas of abundant sand and show a complex internal structure.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Careful 3-D mapping is required to determine the morphology of a draa preserved in the geologic record.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Linear dunes can be traced up to tens of kilometers, with heights sometimes in excess of 70 meters (230 ft).
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] They are typically several hundred meters across and are spaced 1 to 2 kilometers (0.62 to 1.24 mi) apart.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] They sometimes coalesce at a Y-junction with the fork directed upwind.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] They have a sharp sinuous or en echelon crest.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] They are thought to form from a bimodal seasonal wind pattern, with a weak wind season characterized by wind directed an at acute angle to the prevailing winds of the strong wind season.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The strong wind season produces a barchan form and the weak wind season stretches this into the linear form.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Another possibility is that these dunes result from secondary flow, though the precise mechanism remains uncertain.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Complex dunes (star dunes or rhourd dunes) are characterized by having more than two slip faces.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] They consist of a central peak with radiating crests and are thought to form where strong winds can come from any direction.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Those in Gran Desierto de Altar of Mexico are thought to have formed from precursor linear dunes due to a change in the wind pattern about 3000 years ago.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Complex dunes show little lateral growth but strong vertical growth and are important sand sinks.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Vegetated parabolic dunes are crescent-shaped, but the ends of the crescent point upwind, not downwind.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] They form from the interaction of vegetation patches with active sand sources, such as blowouts.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The vegetation stabilizes the arms of the dune, and an elongated lake sometimes forms between the arms of the dune.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Clay dunes are uncommon but have been found in Africa, Australia, and along the Gulf Coast of North America.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] These form on mud flats on the margins of saline bodies of water subject to strong prevailing winds during a dry season.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Clay particles are bound into sand-sized pellets by salts and are then deposited in the dunes, where the return of the cool season allows the pellets to absorb moisture and become bound to the dune surface.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Deserts cover 20 to 25 percent of the modern land surface of the earth, mostly between the latitudes of 10 to 30 degrees north or south.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Here the descending part of the tropical atmospheric circulation (the Hadley cell) produces high atmospheric pressure and suppresses precipitation.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Large areas of this desert is floored with windblown sand.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Such areas are called *ergs* when they exceed about 125 square kilometers (48 sq mi) in area or *dune fields* when smaller.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Ergs and dune fields make up about 20% of modern deserts or about 6% of the Earth's total land surface.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The sandy areas of today's world are somewhat anomalous.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Deserts, in both the present day and in the geological record, are usually dominated by alluvial fans rather than dune fields.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The present relative abundance of sandy areas may reflect reworking of Tertiary sediments following the Last Glacial Maximum.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Most modern deserts have experienced extreme Quaternary climate change, and the sediments that are now being churned by wind systems were generated in upland areas during previous pluvial (moist) periods and transported to depositional basins by stream flow.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The sediments, already sorted during their initial fluvial transport, were further sorted by wind, which also sculpted the sediments into eolian landforms.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The state of an aeolian system depends mainly on three things: The amount of sediment supply, the availability of sediments, and the transport capacity of the winds.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The sediment supply is largely produced in pluvial periods (periods of greater rainfall) and accumulates by runoff as fan deltas or terminal fans in sedimentary basins.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Another important source of sediments is the reworking of carbonate sediments on continental shelves exposed during times of lower sea level.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Sediment availability depends on the coarseness of the local sediment supply, the degree of exposure of sediment grains, the amount of soil moisture, and the extent of vegetation coverage.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The potential transport rate of wind is usually more than the actual transport, because the sediment supply is usually insufficient to saturate the wind.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] In other words, most aeolian systems are *transport-undersaturated* (or *sediment-undersaturated*).
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Aeolian desert systems can be divided into wet, dry, or stabilized systems.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Dry systems have the water table well below the surface, where it has no stabilizing effect on sediments.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Dune shapes determine whether sediment is deposited, simply moves across surface (a *bypass* system), or erosion takes place.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Wet systems are characterized by a water table near the depositional surface, which exerts a strong control on deposition, bypass, or erosion.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Stabilized systems have significant vegetation, surface cement, or mud drapes which dominate the evolution of the system.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The Sahara shows the full range of all three types.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The movement of sediments in aeolian systems can be represented by sand-flow maps.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] These are based on meteorological observations, bedform orientations, and trends of yardangs.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] They are analogous to drainage maps, but are not as closely tied to topography, since wind can blow sand significant distances uphill.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The Sahara of North Africa is the largest hot desert in the world.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Flowlines can be traced from erg to erg, demonstrating very long transport downwind.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Satellite observations show yardangs aligned with the sandflow lines.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] All flowlines arise in the desert itself, and show indications of clockwise circulation roughly like high pressure cells.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The greatest deflation occurs in dried lake beds where trade winds form a low-level jet between the Tibesti Mountains and the Ennedi Plateau.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The flowlines eventually reach the, sea creating great plume of Saharan dust extending thousands of kilometers into the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] This creates a steady rain of silt into the ocean.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] It is estimated that 260 million tons of sediments are transported through this system each year, but the amount was much greater during the Last Glacial Maximum, based on deep-sea cores.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Mineral dust of 0.1–1 microns in size is a good shortwave radiation scatterer and has a cooling effect on climate.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Another example of an aeolian system is the arid interior of Australia.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] With few topographic barriers to sand movement, an anticlockwise wind system is traced by systems of longitudinal dunes.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The Namib and Oman ergs are fed by coastal sediments.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The Namib receives its sediments from the south through narrow deflation corridors from coast that cross more than 100 kilometers (62 mi) of bedrock to the erg.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The Oman was created by deflation of marine shelf carbonates during the last Pleistocene lowstand of the sea.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The Loess Plateau of China has been a long-term sink for sediments during the Quaternary ice age.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] It provides a record of glaciation, in the form of glacial loess layers separated by paleosols (fossil soils).
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The loess layers were desposited by a strong northwest winter monsoon, while the paleosols record the influence of a moist southeast monsoon.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The African savannah is mostly ergs deposited during the Last Glacial Maximum that are now stabilized by vegetation.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Aeolian processes can be discerned at work in the geologic record as long ago as the Precambrian.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Aeolian formations are prominent in the Paleozoic and Mesozoic of the western US.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Perhaps the best examples of aeolian processes in the geologic record are the Jurassic ergs of the western US.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] These include the Wingate Sandstone, the Navajo Sandstone, and the Page Sandstone.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Individual formations are separated by regional unconformities indicate erg stabilization.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The ergs interfingered with adjacent river systems, as with the Wingate Sandstone interfingering with the Moenave Formation and the Navajo Sandstone with the Kayenta Formation.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The Navajo and Nugget Sandstones were part of the largest erg deposit in the geologic record.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] These formations are up to 700 meters (2,300 ft) thick and are exposed over 265,000 square kilometers (102,000 sq mi).
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Their original extent was likely 2.5 times the present outcrop area.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Though once thought to possibly be marine in origin, they are now all but universally regarded as aeolian deposits.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] They are made up mostly of fine- to medium-sized quartz grains that are well-rounded and frosted, both indications of aeolian transport.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The Navajo contains huge tabular crossbed sets with sweeping foresets.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Individual crossbed sets dip at an angle of more than 20 degrees and are from 5 to 35 meters (16 to 115 ft) thick.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The formation contains freshwater invertebrate fossils and vertebrate tracks.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Slump structures (contorted bedding) are present that resemble those in modern wetted dunes.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Successive migrating dunes deposited a vertical stacking of eolian beds between interdune bounding surfaces and regional supersurfaces.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The Permian Rotliegend Group of the North Sea and north Europe contains sediments from adjacent uplands.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Erg sand bodies within the group are up to 500 meters (1,600 ft) thick.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Study of the crossbedding shows that sediments were deposited by a clockwise atmospheric cell.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Drilling core show dry and wet interdune surfaces and regional supersurfaces, and provide evidence of five or more cycles of erg expansion and contraction.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] A global rise in sea level finally drowned the erg and deposited the beds of the Weissliegend.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The Cedar Mesa Sandstone in Utah was contemporary with the Rogliegend.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] This formation records at least 12 erg sequences bounded by regional deflation supersurfaces.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] Aeolian landforms preserved in the formation range from damp sandsheet and lake paleosol (fossil soil) beds to thin, chaotically arranged dune sets to equilibrium erg construction, with dunes 300 to 400 meters (980 to 1,310 ft) wide migrating over still larger draas.
[src:atmosphere/aeolian-processes] The draas survived individual climate cycles, and their interdunes were sites of barchan nucleation during arid portions of the climate cycles.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] In most circumstances, atmospheric pressure is closely approximated by the hydrostatic pressure caused by the weight of air above the measurement point.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] As elevation increases, there is less overlying atmospheric mass, so atmospheric pressure decreases with increasing elevation.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Because the atmosphere is thin relative to the Earth's radius – especially the dense atmospheric layer at low altitudes – the Earth's gravitational acceleration as a function of altitude can be approximated as constant and contributes little to this fall-off.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Pressure measures force per unit area, with SI units of pascals (1 pascal = 1 newton per square meter, 1 N/m2).
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] A column of air with a cross-sectional area of 1 in2 would have a weight of about 14.7 lbf, resulting in a pressure of 14.7 lbf/in2.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Atmospheric pressure is caused by the gravitational attraction of the planet on the atmospheric gases above the surface and is a function of the mass of the planet, the radius of the surface, and the amount and composition of the gases and their vertical distribution in the atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] It is modified by the planetary rotation and local effects such as wind velocity, density variations due to temperature and variations in composition.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] The *mean sea-level pressure* (MSLP) is the atmospheric pressure at mean sea level.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] This is the atmospheric pressure normally given in weather reports via meteorologists on radio, television, and newspapers or on the Internet.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] The *altimeter setting* in aviation is an atmospheric pressure adjustment.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] In aviation weather reports (METAR), QNH is transmitted around the world in hectopascals or millibars (1 hectopascal = 1 millibar).
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] In the United States, Canada, and Japan altimeter setting is reported in inches of mercury (to two decimal places).
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] The United States and Canada also report *sea-level pressure* SLP, which is adjusted to sea level by a different method, in the remarks section, not in the internationally transmitted part of the code, in hectopascals or millibars.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] However, in Canada's public weather reports, sea level pressure is instead reported in kilopascals.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] In the US weather code remarks, three digits are all that are transmitted; decimal points and the one or two most significant digits are omitted: 1,013.2 hPa (14.695 psi) is transmitted as 132; 1,000 hPa (100 kPa) is transmitted as 000; 998.7 hPa is transmitted as 987; etc.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] A system transmitting the last three digits transmits the same code (800) for 1080.0 hPa as for 980.0 hPa.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] The highest *sea-level pressure* on Earth occurs in Siberia, where the Siberian High often attains a *sea-level pressure* above 1,050 hPa (15.2 psi; 31 inHg), with record highs close to 1,085 hPa (15.74 psi; 32.0 inHg).
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] The lowest measurable *sea-level pressure* is found at the centres of tropical cyclones and tornadoes, with a record low of 870 hPa (12.6 psi; 26 inHg).
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] For numerical reasons, atmospheric models such as general circulation models (GCMs) usually predict the nondimensional *logarithm of surface pressure*.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] The average value of surface pressure on Earth is 985 hPa.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] This is in contrast to mean sea-level pressure, which involves the extrapolation of pressure to sea level for locations above or below sea level.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] The average pressure at mean sea level (MSL) in the International Standard Atmosphere (ISA) is 1,013.25 hPa, or 1 atmosphere (atm), or 29.92 inches of mercury.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Pressure (P), mass (m), and acceleration due to gravity (g) are related by P = F/A = (m*g)/A, where A is the surface area.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Atmospheric pressure is thus proportional to the weight per unit area of the atmospheric mass above that location.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Pressure on Earth varies with the altitude of the surface, so air pressure on mountains is usually lower than air pressure at sea level.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Pressure varies smoothly from the Earth's surface to the top of the mesosphere.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Although the pressure changes with the weather, NASA has averaged the conditions for all parts of the earth year-round.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] As altitude increases, atmospheric pressure decreases.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] One can calculate the atmospheric pressure at a given altitude.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Temperature and humidity also affect the atmospheric pressure.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Pressure is proportional to temperature and inversely related to humidity, and both of these are necessary to compute an accurate figure.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] The graph on the rightabove was developed for a temperature of 15 °C and a relative humidity of 0%.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] At low altitudes above sea level, the pressure decreases by about 1.2 kPa (12 hPa) for every 100 meters.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Atmospheric pressure varies widely on Earth, and differences in pressure are important in studying weather and climate.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Some variations in pressure are very regular.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] One important source of variation is atmospheric tides.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Atmospheric tides are strongest in tropical zones, with an amplitude of a few hectopascals, and almost zero in polar areas.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Tropical tidal variations in pressure consist principally of two superimposed harmonics – a circadian (24 h) cycle and a semi-circadian (12 h) cycle.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] The highest adjusted-to-sea level barometric pressure ever recorded on Earth above 750 meters was 1,084.8 hPa (32.03 inHg; 1.0706 atm), measured in Tosontsengel, Mongolia on 19 December 2001.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] The highest adjusted-to-sea level barometric pressure ever recorded below 750 meters was at Agata, in Evenk Autonomous Okrug, Russia (66°53' N, 93°28' E, elevation: 261 m, 856 ft), on 31 December 1968 of 1,083.8 hPa (32.005 inHg).
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] The Dead Sea, the lowest sea surface on Earth, at 430 metres (1,410 ft) below sea level, has a correspondingly high typical atmospheric pressure of 1,065 hPa.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] A below-sea-level surface pressure record of 1,081.8 hPa (31.95 inHg; 1.0677 atm) was set on 21 February 1961.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] The lowest non-tornadic atmospheric pressure ever measured was 870 hPa (26 inHg; 0.86 atm), set on 12 October 1979, during Typhoon Tip in the western Pacific Ocean.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] The measurement was based on an instrumental observation made from a reconnaissance aircraft.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] One atmosphere (101.325 kPa or 14.7 psi) is also the pressure caused by the weight of a column of freshwater of approximately 10.3 m (33.8 ft).
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Thus, a diver 10.3 m under water experiences a pressure of about 2 atmospheres (1 atm of air plus 1 atm of water).
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Conversely, 10.3 m is the maximum height to which water can be raised using suction under standard atmospheric conditions.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Low pressures, such as natural gas lines, are sometimes specified in inches of water, typically written as *w.c.* (water column) gauge or *w.g.* (inches water) gauge.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] A typical gas-using residential appliance in the US is rated for a maximum of 1⁄2 psi (3.4 kPa; 34 mbar), which is approximately 14 w.g.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Similar metric units with a wide variety of names and notation based on millimeters, centimeters or meters are now less commonly used.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Pure water boils at 100 °C (212 °F) at Earth's standard atmospheric pressure.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] The boiling point is the temperature at which the vapour pressure is equal to the atmospheric pressure around the liquid.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Because of this, the boiling point of liquids is lower at lower pressure and higher at higher pressure.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Cooking at high elevations, therefore, requires adjustments to recipes or pressure cooking.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] A rough approximation of elevation can be obtained by measuring the temperature at which water boils; in the mid-19th century, this method was used by explorers.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] Conversely, if one wishes to evaporate a liquid at a lower temperature, for example in distillation, the atmospheric pressure may be lowered by using a vacuum pump, as in a rotary evaporator.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] An important application of the knowledge that atmospheric pressure varies directly with altitude was in determining the height of hills and mountains, thanks to reliable pressure measurement devices.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] In 1774, Nevil Maskelyne was confirming Newton's theory of gravitation at and on Schiehallion mountain in Scotland, and he needed to measure elevations on the mountain's sides accurately.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] This event is known as the Schiehallion experiment.
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] William Roy, using barometric pressure, was able to confirm Maskelyne's height determinations; the agreement was within one meter (3.28 feet).
[src:atmosphere/air-pressure] This method became and continues to be useful for survey work and map making.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] While directional-hemispherical reflectance factor is calculated for a single angle of incidence (i.e., for a given position of the Sun), albedo is the directional integration of reflectance over all solar angles in a given period.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The temporal resolution may range from seconds (as obtained from flux measurements) to daily, monthly, or annual averages.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Unless given for a specific wavelength (spectral albedo), albedo refers to the entire spectrum of solar radiation.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Due to measurement constraints, it is often given for the spectrum in which most solar energy reaches the surface (between 0.3 and 3 μm).
[src:atmosphere/albedo] This spectrum includes visible light (0.4–0.7 μm), which explains why surfaces with a low albedo appear dark (e.g., trees absorb most radiation), whereas surfaces with a high albedo appear bright (e.g., snow reflects most radiation).
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Ice–albedo feedback is a positive feedback climate process where a change in the area of ice caps, glaciers, and sea ice alters the albedo and surface temperature of a planet.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Ice is very reflective, therefore it reflects far more solar energy back to space than the other types of land area or open water.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Ice–albedo feedback plays an important role in global climate change.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Albedo is an important concept in climate science.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The albedo in visible light ranges from about 0.9 to 0.95 for fresh snow to about 0.04 for charcoal, one of the darkest substances.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Deeply shadowed cavities can achieve an effective albedo approaching the zero of a black body.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] When seen from a distance, the ocean surface has a low albedo, as do most forests, whereas desert areas have some of the highest albedos among landforms.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Most land areas are in an albedo range of 0.1 to 0.4.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The average albedo of Earth is about 0.3.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] This is far higher than for the ocean primarily because of the contribution of clouds.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Earth's surface albedo is regularly estimated via Earth observation satellite sensors such as NASA's MODIS instruments on board the Terra and Aqua satellites, and the CERES instrument on the Suomi NPP and JPSS.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] These calculations are based on the bidirectional reflectance distribution function (BRDF), which describes how the reflectance of a given surface depends on the view angle of the observer and the solar angle.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] BDRF can facilitate translations of observations of reflectance into albedo.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Earth's average surface temperature due to its albedo and the greenhouse effect is currently about 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:atmosphere/albedo] If Earth were frozen entirely (and hence be more reflective), the average temperature of the planet would drop below −40 °C (−40 °F).
[src:atmosphere/albedo] If only the continental land masses became covered by glaciers, the mean temperature of the planet would drop to about 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:atmosphere/albedo] In contrast, if the entire Earth was covered by water – a so-called ocean planet – the average temperature on the planet would rise to almost 27 °C (81 °F).
[src:atmosphere/albedo] In 2021, scientists reported that Earth dimmed by ~0.5% over two decades (1998–2017) as measured by earthshine using modern photometric techniques.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] This may have both been co-caused by climate change as well as a substantial increase in global warming.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] However, the link to climate change has not been explored to date and it is unclear whether or not this represents an ongoing trend.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] This formula is important because it allows the albedo to be calculated for any given illumination conditions from a knowledge of the intrinsic properties of the surface.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Human activities (e.g., deforestation, farming, and urbanization) change the albedo of various areas around the globe.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Human impacts to "the physical properties of the land surface can perturb the climate by altering the Earth's radiative energy balance" even on a small scale or when undetected by satellites.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Urbanization generally decreases albedo (commonly being 0.01–0.02 lower than adjacent croplands), which contributes to global warming.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Deliberately increasing albedo in urban areas can mitigate the urban heat island effect.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Intentionally enhancing the albedo of the Earth's surface, along with its daytime thermal emittance, has been proposed as a solar radiation management strategy to mitigate energy crises and global warming known as passive daytime radiative cooling (PDRC).
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Efforts toward widespread implementation of PDRCs may focus on maximizing the albedo of surfaces from very low to high values, so long as a thermal emittance of at least 90% can be achieved.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The tens of thousands of hectares of greenhouses in Almería, Spain form a large expanse of whitened plastic roofs.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] A 2008 study found that this anthropogenic change lowered the local surface area temperature of the high-albedo area, although changes were localized.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] A follow-up study found that "CO2-eq. emissions associated to changes in surface albedo are a consequence of land transformation" and can reduce surface temperature increases associated with climate change.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] However, albedo and illumination both vary by latitude.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Albedo is highest near the poles and lowest in the subtropics, with a local maximum in the tropics.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Tropical and sub-tropical rainforest areas have low albedo, and are much hotter than their temperate forest counterparts, which have lower insolation.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Because insolation plays such a big role in the heating and cooling effects of albedo, high insolation areas like the tropics will tend to show a more pronounced fluctuation in local temperature when local albedo changes.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Arctic regions notably release more heat back into space than what they absorb, effectively cooling the Earth.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Since arctic ice and snow have been melting at higher rates due to higher temperatures, creating regions in the arctic that are notably darker (being water or ground which is darker color), there is concern because less heat is reflected back into space.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] This feedback loop results in a reduced albedo effect.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Albedo affects climate by determining how much radiation a planet absorbs.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The uneven heating of Earth from albedo variations between land, ice, or ocean surfaces can drive weather.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The response of the climate system to an initial forcing is modified by feedbacks: increased by "self-reinforcing" or "positive" feedbacks and reduced by "balancing" or "negative" feedbacks.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The main reinforcing feedbacks are the water-vapour feedback, the ice–albedo feedback, and the net effect of clouds.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] When an area's albedo changes due to snowfall, a snow–temperature feedback results.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] A layer of snowfall increases local albedo, reflecting away sunlight, leading to local cooling.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] In principle, if no outside temperature change affects this area (e.g., a warm air mass), the raised albedo and lower temperature would maintain the current snow and invite further snowfall, deepening the snow–temperature feedback.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] However, because local weather is dynamic due to the change of seasons, eventually warm air masses and a more direct angle of sunlight (higher insolation) cause melting.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] When the melted area reveals surfaces with lower albedo, such as grass, soil, or ocean, the effect is reversed: the darkening surface lowers albedo, increasing local temperatures, which induces more melting and thus reducing the albedo further, resulting in still more heating.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Snow albedo is highly variable, ranging from as high as 0.9 for freshly fallen snow, to about 0.4 for melting snow, and as low as 0.2 for dirty snow.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Over Antarctica, snow albedo averages a little more than 0.8.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] If a marginally snow-covered area warms, snow tends to melt, lowering the albedo, and hence leading to more snowmelt because more radiation is being absorbed by the snowpack (referred to as the ice–albedo positive feedback).
[src:atmosphere/albedo] In Switzerland, the citizens have been protecting their glaciers with large white tarpaulins to slow down the ice melt.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] These large white sheets are helping to reject the rays from the sun and defecting the heat.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Although this method is very expensive, it has been shown to work, reducing snow and ice melt by 60%.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Just as fresh snow has a higher albedo than does dirty snow, the albedo of snow-covered sea ice is far higher than that of sea water.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Sea water absorbs more solar radiation than would the same surface covered with reflective snow.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] When sea ice melts, either due to a rise in sea temperature or in response to increased solar radiation from above, the snow-covered surface is reduced, and more surface of sea water is exposed, so the rate of energy absorption increases.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The extra absorbed energy heats the sea water, which in turn increases the rate at which sea ice melts.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] As with the preceding example of snowmelt, the process of melting of sea ice is thus another example of a positive feedback.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Both positive feedback loops have long been recognized as important for global warming.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Cryoconite, powdery windblown dust containing soot, sometimes reduces albedo on glaciers and ice sheets.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The dynamical nature of albedo in response to positive feedback, together with the effects of small errors in the measurement of albedo, can lead to large errors in energy estimates.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Because of this, in order to reduce the error of energy estimates, it is important to measure the albedo of snow-covered areas through remote sensing techniques rather than applying a single value for albedo over broad regions.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] In sunlight, dark clothes absorb more heat and light-coloured clothes reflect it better, thus allowing some control over body temperature by exploiting the albedo effect of the colour of external clothing.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Albedo can affect the electrical energy output of solar photovoltaic devices.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Research showed impacts of over 10% for vertically (90°) mounted systems, but such effects were substantially lower for systems with lower surface tilts.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Spectral albedo strongly affects the performance of bifacial solar cells where rear surface performance gains of over 20% have been observed for c-Si cells installed above healthy vegetation.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Forests generally have a low albedo because the majority of the ultraviolet and visible spectrum is absorbed through photosynthesis.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] For this reason, the greater heat absorption by trees could offset some of the carbon benefits of afforestation (or offset the negative climate impacts of deforestation).
[src:atmosphere/albedo] In other words: The climate change mitigation effect of carbon sequestration by forests is partially counterbalanced in that reforestation can decrease the reflection of sunlight (albedo).
[src:atmosphere/albedo] In the case of evergreen forests with seasonal snow cover, albedo reduction may be significant enough for deforestation to cause a net cooling effect.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Trees also impact climate in extremely complicated ways through evapotranspiration.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The water vapor causes cooling on the land surface, causes heating where it condenses, acts as strong greenhouse gas, and can increase albedo when it condenses into clouds.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Scientists generally treat evapotranspiration as a net cooling impact, and the net climate impact of albedo and evapotranspiration changes from deforestation depends greatly on local climate.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Mid-to-high-latitude forests have a much lower albedo during snow seasons than flat ground, thus contributing to warming.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Modeling that compares the effects of albedo differences between forests and grasslands suggests that expanding the land area of forests in temperate zones offers only a temporary mitigation benefit.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] In seasonally snow-covered zones, winter albedos of treeless areas are 10% to 50% higher than nearby forested areas because snow does not cover the trees as readily.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Deciduous trees have an albedo value of about 0.15 to 0.18 whereas coniferous trees have a value of about 0.09 to 0.15.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Variation in summer albedo across both forest types is associated with maximum rates of photosynthesis because plants with high growth capacity display a greater fraction of their foliage for direct interception of incoming radiation in the upper canopy.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The result is that wavelengths of light not used in photosynthesis are more likely to be reflected back to space rather than being absorbed by other surfaces lower in the canopy.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Studies by the Hadley Centre have investigated the relative (generally warming) effect of albedo change and (cooling) effect of carbon sequestration on planting forests.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] They found that new forests in tropical and midlatitude areas tended to cool; new forests in high latitudes (e.g., Siberia) were neutral or perhaps warming.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Research in 2023, drawing from 176 flux stations globally, revealed a climate trade-off: increased carbon uptake from afforestation results in reduced albedo.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Initially, this reduction may lead to moderate global warming over a span of approximately 20 years, but it is expected to transition into significant cooling thereafter.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Water reflects light very differently from typical terrestrial materials.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The reflectivity of a water surface is calculated using the Fresnel equations.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] At the scale of the wavelength of light even wavy water is always smooth so the light is reflected in a locally specular manner (not diffusely).
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The glint of light off water is a commonplace effect of this.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] At small angles of incident light, waviness results in reduced reflectivity because of the steepness of the reflectivity-vs.-incident-angle curve and a locally increased average incident angle.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Although the reflectivity of water is very low at low and medium angles of incident light, it becomes very high at high angles of incident light such as those that occur on the illuminated side of Earth near the terminator (early morning, late afternoon, and near the poles).
[src:atmosphere/albedo] However, as mentioned above, waviness causes an appreciable reduction.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Because light specularly reflected from water does not usually reach the viewer, water is usually considered to have a very low albedo in spite of its high reflectivity at high angles of incident light.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Note that white caps on waves look white (and have high albedo) because the water is foamed up, so there are many superimposed bubble surfaces which reflect, adding up their reflectivities.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Fresh 'black' ice exhibits Fresnel reflection.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Snow on top of this sea ice increases the albedo to 0.9.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Cloud albedo has substantial influence over atmospheric temperatures.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Different types of clouds exhibit different reflectivity, theoretically ranging in albedo from a minimum of near 0 to a maximum approaching 0.8.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] "On any given day, about half of Earth is covered by clouds, which reflect more sunlight than land and water.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Albedo and climate in some areas are affected by artificial clouds, such as those created by the contrails of heavy commercial airliner traffic.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] A study following the burning of the Kuwaiti oil fields during Iraqi occupation showed that temperatures under the burning oil fires were as much as 10 °C (18 °F) colder than temperatures several miles away under clear skies.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Aerosols (very fine particles/droplets in the atmosphere) have both direct and indirect effects on Earth's radiative balance.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The direct (albedo) effect is generally to cool the planet; the indirect effect (the particles act as cloud condensation nuclei and thereby change cloud properties) is less certain.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Another albedo-related effect on the climate is from black carbon particles.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The size of this effect is difficult to quantify: the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that the global mean radiative forcing for black carbon aerosols from fossil fuels is +0.2 W m−2, with a range +0.1 to +0.4 W m−2.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Black carbon is a bigger cause of the melting of the polar ice cap in the Arctic than carbon dioxide due to its effect on the albedo.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] In astronomy, the term **albedo** can be defined in several different ways, depending upon the application and the wavelength of electromagnetic radiation involved.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The albedos of planets, satellites and minor planets such as asteroids can be used to infer much about their properties.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The study of albedos, their dependence on wavelength, lighting angle ("phase angle"), and variation in time composes a major part of the astronomical field of photometry.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] For small and far objects that cannot be resolved by telescopes, much of what we know comes from the study of their albedos.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] For example, the absolute albedo can indicate the surface ice content of outer Solar System objects, the variation of albedo with phase angle gives information about regolith properties, whereas unusually high radar albedo is indicative of high metal content in asteroids.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Enceladus, a moon of Saturn, has one of the highest known optical albedos of any body in the Solar System, with an albedo of 0.99.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Another notable high-albedo body is Eris, with an albedo of 0.96.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Many small objects in the outer Solar System and asteroid belt have low albedos down to about 0.05.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] A typical comet nucleus has an albedo of 0.04.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Such a dark surface is thought to be indicative of a primitive and heavily space weathered surface containing some organic compounds.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The overall albedo of the Moon is measured to be around 0.14, but it is strongly directional and non-Lambertian, displaying also a strong opposition effect.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Although such reflectance properties are different from those of any terrestrial terrains, they are typical of the regolith surfaces of airless Solar System bodies.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Two common optical albedos that are used in astronomy are the (V-band) geometric albedo (measuring brightness when illumination comes from directly behind the observer) and the Bond albedo (measuring total proportion of electromagnetic energy reflected).
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Their values can differ significantly, which is a common source of confusion.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] In detailed studies, the directional reflectance properties of astronomical bodies are often expressed in terms of the five Hapke parameters which semi-empirically describe the variation of albedo with phase angle, including a characterization of the opposition effect of regolith surfaces.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] One of these five parameters is yet another type of albedo called the single-scattering albedo.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] It is used to define scattering of electromagnetic waves on small particles.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] It depends on properties of the material (refractive index), the size of the particle, and the wavelength of the incoming radiation.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] An important relationship between an object's astronomical (geometric) albedo, absolute magnitude and diameter is given by: $A=\left({\frac {1329\times 10^{-H/5}}{D}}\right)^{2},$ where A is the astronomical albedo, D is the diameter in kilometers, and H is the absolute magnitude.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] In planetary radar astronomy, a microwave (or radar) pulse is transmitted toward a planetary target (e.g.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Moon, asteroid, etc.) and the echo from the target is measured.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] In most instances, the transmitted pulse is circularly polarized and the received pulse is measured in the same sense of polarization as the transmitted pulse (SC) and the opposite sense (OC).
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The echo power is measured in terms of radar cross-section, ${\sigma }_{OC}$ , ${\sigma }_{SC}$ , or ${\sigma }_{T}$ (total power, SC + OC) and is equal to the cross-sectional area of a metallic sphere (perfect reflector) at the same distance as the target that would return the same echo power.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] Those components of the received echo that return from first-surface reflections (as from a smooth or mirror-like surface) are dominated by the OC component as there is a reversal in polarization upon reflection.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] If the surface is rough at the wavelength scale or there is significant penetration into the regolith, there will be a significant SC component in the echo caused by multiple scattering.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] where the denominator is the effective cross-sectional area of the target object with mean radius, r .
[src:atmosphere/albedo] A smooth metallic sphere would have ${\hat {\sigma }}_{\text{OC}}=1$ .
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The values reported for the Moon, Mercury, Mars, Venus, and Comet P/2005 JQ5 are derived from the total (OC+SC) radar albedo reported in those references.
[src:atmosphere/albedo] The term albedo was introduced into optics by Johann Heinrich Lambert in his 1760 work *Photometria*.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek was the language of Homer and of fifth-century Athenian historians, playwrights, and philosophers.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] It has contributed many words to English vocabulary and has been a standard subject of study in educational institutions of the Western world since the Renaissance.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] This article primarily contains information about the Epic and Classical periods of the language, which are the best-attested periods and considered most typical of Ancient Greek.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek comprised several dialects, such as Attic, Ionic, Doric, Aeolic, and Arcadocypriot; among them, Attic Greek became the basis of Koine Greek.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Just like Koine is often included in Ancient Greek, conversely, Mycenaean Greek is usually treated separately and not always included in Ancient Greek – reflecting the fact that Greek in the first millennium BC is considered prototypical of Ancient Greek.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek was a pluricentric language, divided into many dialects.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] The main dialect groups are Attic and Ionic, Aeolic, Arcadocypriot, and Doric, many of them with several subdivisions.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Some dialects are found in standardized literary forms in literature, while others are attested only in inscriptions.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] There are also several historical forms.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Homeric Greek is a literary form of Archaic Greek (derived primarily from Ionic and Aeolic) used in the epic poems, the *Iliad* and the *Odyssey*, and in later poems by other authors.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Homeric Greek had significant differences in grammar and pronunciation from Classical Attic and other Classical-era dialects.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] The origins, early form and development of the Hellenic language family are not well understood because of a lack of contemporaneous evidence.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Several theories exist about what Hellenic dialect groups may have existed between the divergence of early Greek-like speech from the common Proto-Indo-European language and the Classical period.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] They have the same general outline but differ in some of the detail.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] The only attested dialect from this period is Mycenaean Greek, but its relationship to the historical dialects and the historical circumstances of the times imply that the overall groups already existed in some form.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Scholars assume that major Ancient Greek period dialect groups developed no later than 1120 BC, at the time of the Dorian invasions—and that their first appearances as precise alphabetic writing began in the 8th century BC.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] The invasion would not be "Dorian" unless the invaders had some cultural relationship to the historical Dorians.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] The invasion is known to have displaced population to the later Attic-Ionic regions, who regarded themselves as descendants of the population displaced by or contending with the Dorians.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] The Greeks of this period believed there were three major divisions of all Greek people – Dorians, Aeolians, and Ionians (including Athenians), each with their own defining and distinctive dialects.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Allowing for their oversight of Arcadian, an obscure mountain dialect, and Cypriot, far from the center of Greek scholarship, this division of people and language is quite similar to the results of modern archaeological-linguistic investigation.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] (Southern Italy and Sicily) in the classical period.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] West vs. non-West Greek is the strongest-marked and earliest division, with non-West in subsets of Ionic-Attic (or Attic-Ionic) and Aeolic vs.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Arcadocypriot, or Aeolic and Arcado-Cypriot vs.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Arcadocypriot apparently descended more closely from the Mycenaean Greek of the Bronze Age.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Boeotian Greek had come under a strong Northwest Greek influence, and can in some respects be considered a transitional dialect, as exemplified in the poems of the Boeotian poet Pindar who wrote in Doric with a small Aeolic admixture.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Thessalian likewise had come under Northwest Greek influence, though to a lesser degree.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Pamphylian Greek, spoken in a small area on the southwestern coast of Anatolia and little preserved in inscriptions, may be either a fifth major dialect group, or it is Mycenaean Greek overlaid by Doric, with a non-Greek native influence.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Based on the conclusions drawn by several studies and findings such as Pella curse tablet, Emilio Crespo and most scholars suggest that ancient Macedonian was a Northwest Doric dialect, which shares isoglosses with its neighboring Thessalian dialects spoken in northeastern Thessaly.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Some have also suggested an Aeolic Greek classification.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] For example, fragments of the works of the poet Sappho from the island of Lesbos are in Aeolian.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Most of the dialect sub-groups listed above had further subdivisions, generally equivalent to a city-state and its surrounding territory, or to an island.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Doric notably had several intermediate divisions as well, into Island Doric (including Cretan Doric), Southern Peloponnesus Doric (including Laconian, the dialect of Sparta), and Northern Peloponnesus Doric (including Corinthian).
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] All the groups were represented by colonies beyond Greece proper as well, and these colonies generally developed local characteristics, often under the influence of settlers or neighbors speaking different Greek dialects.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] After the conquests of Alexander the Great in the late 4th century BC, a new international dialect known as Koine or Common Greek developed, largely based on Attic Greek, but with influence from other dialects.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] This dialect slowly replaced most of the older dialects, although the Doric dialect has survived in the Tsakonian language, which is spoken in the region of modern Sparta.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Doric has also passed down its aorist terminations into most verbs of Demotic Greek.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] By about the 6th century AD, the Koine had slowly metamorphosed into Medieval Greek.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Phrygian is an extinct Indo-European language of West and Central Anatolia, which is regarded by current consensus to have been closely related to Greek.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Among Indo-European branches with living descendants, Greek is often argued to have the closest genetic ties with Armenian (see also Graeco-Armenian) and Indo-Iranian languages (see Graeco-Aryan).
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek differs from Proto-Indo-European (PIE) and other Indo-European languages in certain ways.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] In phonotactics, ancient Greek words could end only in a vowel or /n s r/; final stops were lost, as in γάλα "milk", compared with γάλακτος "of milk" (genitive).
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] The pronunciation of Ancient Greek was very different from that of Modern Greek.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek had long and short vowels; many diphthongs; double and single consonants; voiced, voiceless, and aspirated stops; and a pitch accent.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] In Modern Greek, all vowels and consonants are short.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Many vowels and diphthongs once pronounced distinctly are pronounced as /i/ (iotacism).
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Some of the stops and glides in diphthongs have become fricatives, and the pitch accent has changed to a stress accent.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Many of the changes took place in the Koine Greek period.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] The writing system of Modern Greek, however, does not reflect all pronunciation changes.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] The examples below represent Attic Greek in the 5th century BC.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Ancient pronunciation cannot be reconstructed with certainty, but Greek from the period is well documented, and there is little disagreement among linguists as to the general nature of the sounds that the letters represent.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] /oː/ raised to [uː], probably by the 4th century BC.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Greek, like all of the older Indo-European languages, is highly inflected.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] It is highly archaic in its preservation of Proto-Indo-European forms.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] In ancient Greek, nouns (including proper nouns) have five cases (nominative, genitive, dative, accusative, and vocative), three genders (masculine, feminine, and neuter), and three numbers (singular, dual, and plural).
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Verbs have four moods (indicative, imperative, subjunctive, and optative) and three voices (active, middle, and passive), as well as three persons (first, second, and third) and various other forms.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Verbs are conjugated through seven combinations of tenses and aspect (generally simply called "tenses"): the present, future, and imperfect are imperfective in aspect; the aorist, present perfect, pluperfect and future perfect are perfective in aspect.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Most tenses display all four moods and three voices, although there is no future subjunctive or imperative.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Also, there is no imperfect subjunctive, optative or imperative.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] The infinitives and participles correspond to the finite combinations of tense, aspect, and voice.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] The indicative of past tenses adds (conceptually, at least) a prefix /e-/, called the augment.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] This was probably originally a separate word, meaning something like "then", added because tenses in PIE had primarily aspectual meaning.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] The augment is added to the indicative of the aorist, imperfect, and pluperfect, but not to any of the other forms of the aorist (no other forms of the imperfect and pluperfect exist).
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] The two kinds of augment in Greek are syllabic and quantitative.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] The syllabic augment is added to stems beginning with consonants, and simply prefixes *e* (stems beginning with *r*, however, add *er*).
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Some verbs augment irregularly; the most common variation is *e* → *ei*.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] The irregularity can be explained diachronically by the loss of *s* between vowels, or that of the letter *w*, which affected the augment when it was word-initial.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] In verbs with a preposition as a prefix, the augment is placed not at the start of the word, but between the preposition and the original verb.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] For example, προσ(-)βάλλω (I attack) goes to προσ**έ**βαλoν in the aorist.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] However compound verbs consisting of a prefix that is not a preposition retain the augment at the start of the word: αὐτο(-)μολῶ goes to **ηὐ**τομόλησα in the aorist.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Following Homer's practice, the augment is sometimes not made in poetry, especially epic poetry.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] The augment sometimes substitutes for reduplication; see below.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Almost all forms of the perfect, pluperfect, and future perfect reduplicate the initial syllable of the verb stem.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Irregular duplication can be understood diachronically.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] For example, *lambanō* (root *lab*) has the perfect stem *eilēpha* (not **lelēpha*) because it was originally *slambanō*, with perfect *seslēpha*, becoming *eilēpha* through compensatory lengthening.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Reduplication is also visible in the present tense stems of certain verbs.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] These stems add a syllable consisting of the root's initial consonant followed by *i*.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] A nasal stop appears after the reduplication in some verbs.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] The earliest extant examples of ancient Greek writing (c.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] 1450 BC) are in the syllabic script Linear B.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Beginning in the 8th century BC, however, the Greek alphabet became standard, albeit with some variation among dialects.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Early texts are written in boustrophedon style, but left-to-right became standard during the classic period.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Modern editions of ancient Greek texts are usually written with accents and breathing marks, interword spacing, modern punctuation, and sometimes mixed case, but these were all introduced later.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] The beginning of Apology by Plato exemplifies Attic Greek from the Classical period of ancient Greek.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] How you, men of Athens, are feeling under the power of my accusers, I do not know: actually, even I myself almost forgot who I was because of them, they spoke so persuasively.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] And yet, loosely speaking, nothing they have said is true.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] The study of Ancient Greek in European countries in addition to Latin occupied an important place in the syllabus from the Renaissance until the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] This was true as well in the United States, where many of the nation's founders received a classically based education.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Latin was emphasized in American colleges, but Greek also was required in the colonial and early national eras, and the study of ancient Greece became increasingly popular in the mid-to-late nineteenth century, the age of American philhellenism.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] In particular, female intellectuals of the era designated the mastering of ancient Greek as essential in becoming a "woman of letters".
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is still taught as a compulsory or optional subject especially at traditional or elite schools throughout Europe, such as public schools and grammar schools in the United Kingdom.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] In 2006/07, 15,000 pupils studied ancient Greek in Germany according to the Federal Statistical Office of Germany, and 280,000 pupils studied it in Italy.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] It is a compulsory subject alongside Latin in the humanities branch of the Spanish Baccalaureate.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is taught at most major universities worldwide, often combined with Latin as part of the study of classics.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] In 2010 it was offered in three primary schools in the UK, to boost children's language skills, and was one of seven foreign languages which primary schools could teach 2014 as part of a major drive to boost education standards.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is taught as a compulsory subject in all gymnasiums and lyceums in Greece.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] It appears to have ceased in 2010, having failed to gain the recognition and acceptance of teachers.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Its first issue appeared in April 2015 as an annex to *Hebdomada Aenigmatum*.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Alfred Rahlfs included a preface, a short history of the Septuagint text, and other front matter translated into ancient Greek in his 1935 edition of the Septuagint; Robert Hanhart also included the introductory remarks to the 2006 revised Rahlfs–Hanhart edition in the language as well.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] *Akropolis World News* reports weekly a summary of the most important news in ancient Greek.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is also used by organizations and individuals, mainly Greek, who wish to denote their respect, admiration or preference for the use of this language.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] This use is sometimes considered graphical, nationalistic or humorous.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] In any case, the fact that modern Greeks can still wholly or partly understand texts written in non-archaic forms of ancient Greek shows the affinity of the modern Greek language to its ancestral predecessor.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is often used in the coinage of modern technical terms in the European languages: see English words of Greek origin.
[src:atmosphere/ancient-greek-language] Latinized forms of ancient Greek roots are used in many of the scientific names of species and in scientific terminology.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] An **atmosphere** is a layer of gases that envelop an astronomical object, held in place by the gravity of the object.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The name originates from Ancient Greek ἀτμός*(*atmós*)* 'vapour, steam' and σφαῖρα*(*sphaîra*)* 'sphere'.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] An object acquires most of its atmosphere during its primordial epoch, either by accretion of matter or by outgassing of volatiles.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The chemical interaction of the atmosphere with the solid surface can change its fundamental composition, as can photochemical interaction with the Sun.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] A planet retains an atmosphere for longer durations when the gravity is high and the temperature is low.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The solar wind works to strip away a planet's outer atmosphere, although this process is slowed by a magnetosphere.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The further a body is from the Sun, the lower the rate of atmospheric stripping.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Aside from Mercury, all Solar System planets have substantial atmospheres, as does the dwarf planet Pluto and the moon Titan.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The high gravity and low temperature of Jupiter and the other gas giant planets allow them to retain massive atmospheres of mostly hydrogen and helium.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Lower mass terrestrial planets orbit closer to the Sun, and so mainly retain higher molar mass atmospheres made of carbon, nitrogen, and oxygen, with trace amounts of inert gas.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Atmospheres have been detected around exoplanets such as HD 209458 b and Kepler-7b.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] A stellar atmosphere is the outer region of a star, which includes the layers above the opaque photosphere; stars of low temperature might have outer atmospheres containing compound molecules.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Other objects with atmospheres are brown dwarfs and active comets.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] In the nebular hypothesis, stars form during the gravitational collapse of a mass of gas and dust within an interstellar molecular cloud.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] This material forms a pancake-like rotating disk with the mass concentrated at the center.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The protostar is created at the central mass concentration, while the planets and satellites are formed in the disk through a process of accretion.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Dust settles into the median disk plane, forming materials that can collide and accrete to create planetesimals.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Close to the star, these bodies grow and accumulate to form protoplanets consisting primarily of refractory materials with few volatiles.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Further from the star, planetary embryos are created from accumulation of volatiles up to around ten times the mass of the Earth or more.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Masses of gas are then acquired from the surrounding disk nebula, forming a gas giant around the embryo.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Planetary satellites form in a similar fashion from the disk of material around the planets.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The primary atmosphere of a planet is produced when the gravity is sufficient to retain accreted gas against escape processes.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The latter can include collisions with other bodies that impart sufficient energy for the gasses to escape.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] For the terrestrial planets, the high temperatures generated by their initial bombardment results in the outgassing of volatiles, creating the secondary atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The original composition and thickness of the atmosphere is thus determined by the stellar nebula's chemistry and temperature, but can be modified by processes within the astronomical body that release different atmospheric components.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The circumstellar disk will finally dissipate on time scales of about 107 years, and the star will complete its contraction then ignite hydrogen fusion at its core in a time frame determined by its mass.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The atmospheres of the planets Venus and Mars are principally composed of carbon dioxide, nitrogen, and argon.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Because Venus has no oceans or rain to dissolve the carbon dioxide, large amounts of this greenhouse gas has remained in the atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The result is a dense atmosphere about 80 times the pressure of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The planet's lack of a magnetic field and closer proximity to the Sun resulted in the loss of its hydrogen (in the form of water) after two billion years.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Because Mars is small, cold, and lacks a magnetic field, it has retained only a sparse atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The surface air pressure of 0.6 kPa for Mars is only 0.6% of Earth's 101.3 kPa.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The planet has probably lost at least 80–85% of its original water supply to space.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] However, the planet has retained significant deposits of frozen water and carbon dioxide.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] If all of the frozen CO2 were to sublimate, the air pressure could climb to 30 kPa.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] This is comparable to the air pressure on the top of Mount Everest.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The composition of Earth's atmosphere is determined by the by-products of the life that it sustains.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Dry air (mixture of gases) from Earth's atmosphere contains 78.08% nitrogen, 20.95% oxygen, 0.93% argon, 0.04% carbon dioxide, and traces of hydrogen, helium, and other "noble" gases (by volume), but generally a variable amount of water vapor is also present, on average about 1% at sea level.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Earth's persistent magnetosphere acts as a shield against atmospheric scavenging by the solar wind, as it fends off the incoming plasma at a distance of about 10 Earth radii.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The low temperatures and higher escape velocities of the Solar System's giant planets—Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus and Neptune—allow them more readily to retain gases with low molecular masses.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] These planets have reducing atmospheres of hydrogen and helium, with trace amounts of other elements and more complex compounds.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Unlike the terrestrial planets, the gas giants lack a well-defined surface.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Instead the atmosphere is maintained in hydrostatic equilibrium by intense pressure deep in the body.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The dynamic weather on these bodies only occurs in a relatively thin surface layer.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Two satellites of the outer planets possess significant atmospheres.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Titan, a moon of Saturn, and Triton, a moon of Neptune, have atmospheres mainly of nitrogen.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] When in the part of its orbit closest to the Sun, Pluto has an atmosphere of nitrogen and methane similar to Triton's, but these gases are frozen when it is farther from the Sun.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Other bodies within the Solar System have extremely thin atmospheres not in equilibrium.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] These include the Moon (sodium gas, noble gases, hydrogen), Mercury (sodium gas), Callisto (carbon dioxide and oxygen), Europa (oxygen), Io (sulfur dioxide), and Enceladus (water vapor).
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Planetary objects around distant stars, known as exoplanets, span a more diverse range of physical properties than is found in the Solar System.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] These targets provide an opportunity to study atmospheres around a broad span of objects and conditions.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] However, observations of these targets requires much more sensitive instrumentation.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The methods used to analyze these remote atmospheres are transit spectroscopy, high-resolution Doppler spectroscopy, and direct imaging.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Transit spectroscopy uses the transit of an exoplanet across its host star to detect its atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] By comparing the radius at different wavelengths, the presence of specific components can be detected.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The first such detection was in 2002, when sodium was detected in the atmosphere of HD 209458b, a gas giant with a close orbit around a star in the constellation Pegasus.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Its atmosphere is heated to temperatures over 1,000 K, and is steadily escaping into space.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Hydrogen, oxygen, and carbon have been detected in the planet's inflated atmosphere by Hubble observations.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Since 2002, potassium has been detected in the atmosphere of XO-2Nb, and both sodium and potassium in HD 189733 b's atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Many of the discovered super earths have orbits close enough to their host star that their surfaces are expected to be magma oceans.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The secondary atmospheres of these lava planets most likely consist of materials that have been vaporized from the magma, such as sodium, potassium, oxygen, and silicon oxide.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] An atmosphere in hydrostatic equilibrium consists of a balance between the air pressure created by the motions of the molecules, and the restraining force of gravity that prevents the molecules from escaping.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The pressure decreases in altitude, producing a pressure-gradient force.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Atmospheric pressure is the force (per unit-area) perpendicular to a unit-area of planetary surface, as determined by the weight of the vertical column of atmospheric gases.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] In said atmospheric model, the atmospheric pressure, the weight of the mass of the gas, decreases at high altitude because of the diminishing mass of the gas above the point of barometric measurement.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Air pressure varies by place and time due to meteorological conditions and atmospheric waves.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Units of air pressure are based upon the standard atmosphere (atm), which is 101,325 Pa (equivalent to 760 Torr or 14.696 psi).
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] For an ideal gas atmosphere, the height at which the atmospheric pressure declines by a factor of *e* (the base of the natural logarithm) is called the scale height (*H*).
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] For an atmosphere of uniform temperature, the scale height is proportional to the atmospheric temperature and is inversely proportional to the product of the mean molecular mass of dry air, and the local acceleration of gravity at the point of barometric measurement.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The temperature of the atmosphere is determined by an energy budget, which balances the heating from the incoming solar energy against the heat radiated back into space.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The incoming energy is determined by the distance from the Sun, and the energy reflected back out by the planetary albedo.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] When a planet is in radiative equilibrium, it has a planetary equilibrium temperature.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] This differs from the global mean temperature, which may be warmer than the equilibrium temperature due to the atmospheric greenhouse effect.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] For example, Venus has a surface temperature of almost 460 C compared to an equilibrium temperature of −40 C.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Planetary atmospheres are composed of layers with different properties, such as specific gaseous composition, temperature gradients, and pressure.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] For Earth, Mars, and Venus, the lowest level of the atmosphere is the troposphere, where most of the planet's clouds and weather are found.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] This extends from the ground up to 65 km on Venus, 40 km on Mars, and 17 km on Earth.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The troposphere contains the bulk of the atmosphere, possessing 80%–98% of the total atmospheric mass.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Temperature varies by altitude according to the lapse rate, as thermal energy from the ground is transported upward via convection.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Infrared radiation becomes trapped by molecules of gas and water vapor.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] For the Earth, the next layer is the stratosphere, which is a region of temperature increasing with altitude, creating a temperature inversion.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] This region contains the UV-absorbing ozone layer, at an altitude between 15 km and 35 km, which is responsible for the temperature rise.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Energy transport in this region occurs through radiation processes.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Lacking an oxygenated atmosphere to generate a significant layer of ozone, neither Mars nor Venus have a stratosphere.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Above the troposphere-stratosphere, the next layer of the atmosphere is termed the mesosphere.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] In this region, the water vapor and carbon dioxide serves as a heat sink that radiates energy in the infrared.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] As a result, the temperature of the mesosphere decreases with altitude, reaching the coldest layer of the atmosphere at the top.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Both Venus and Mars have an altitude range in the mesosphere where the temperature is nearly isothermal; for Mars this is above 120 km, while for Venus it is between 63 and 75 km altitude.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] In the lower regions of the atmosphere, turbulent mixing causes the atmospheric constituents to be evenly distributed.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Above a transition layer called the homopause, molecular diffusion dominates.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] This results in diffuse separation of the constituents by atomic weight; that is, lower mass components diffuse upward leaving higher mass molecules near the bottom.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The homopause is at an altitude of 100–110 km for the Earth, 115–130 km for Mars, and 135–150 km for Venus.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Beyond the mesosphere is a region of the atmosphere called the thermosphere that absorbs X-rays and extreme UV from the Sun, causing temperature to rise with altitude.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The thermal properties of this layer vary daily and with solar activity cycles.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The atmospheric region from the ground through the thermosphere is referred to as the barosphere, since the barometric law holds throughout.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The outermost layer of a planetary atmosphere is termed the exosphere.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Here, the air pressure is so low at this altitude that the distance travelled between molecule collisions, the mean free path, is greater than the atmospheric scale height.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] In this region, lower mass components with a thermal velocity exceeding the escape velocity can escape into space.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] For the Earth, the exosphere is at an altitude of 500 km, while it is around 210 km for Venus and Mars.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] On Earth, the exosphere extends to roughly 10,000 km, where it interacts with the magnetosphere of Earth.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] All three planets have an ionosphere, which is an ionized region of the upper atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The ionospheres for Mars and Venus are closer to the surface and are less dense than on the Earth.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The density of the Earth's ionosphere is greater at short distances from the planetary surface in the daytime and decreases as the ionosphere rises at night-time, thereby allowing a greater range of radio frequencies to travel greater distances.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Gas giants are primarily composed of hydrogen and helium with traces of other elements, giving the planets a low bulk density.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Many of the molecules observed in the outer atmosphere are hydrides, and most of these (with the exception of H2O and H2S) are photochemically destroyed by solar UV in the stratosphere of Jupiter and Saturn.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] These compounds get re-created by thermo-chemical reactions within the hotter, lower regions of the atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Complex organic compounds are recycled back to methane by the highly reducing atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The high gravity of these planets combined with their distance from the Sun means that mass loss from their exospheres is negligible, so they form closed systems.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] A common feature of the gas giant planets are cloud layers that form where the combination of temperature and pressure are appropriate for condensing a particular volatile.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] For Jupiter and Saturn, the outermost cloud layer consists of ice particles of ammonia (NH3), with an underlying layer of ammonium hydrosulfide (NH4SH), then a deep layer of water clouds (H2O).
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] For Uranus and Neptune, the top layer is a methane (CH4) layer of ice particles, followed by the same cloud layers as Jupiter and Saturn.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] One difference for Uranus and Neptune is that hydrogen sulfide (H2S) mixes at the same level as the condensed ammonia.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] These cloud layers are optically thick, absorbing light at all wavelengths.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The result is a shallower scale height for the outer atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] All four gas giants experience lightning activity in the water clouds, and this is generally much more powerful than terrestrial lightning.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Lightning has been observed on Jupiter, but has not been optically detected on Saturn, Uranus, or Neptune most likely because of their depth.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] All of the gas giants have internal heat sources and radiate more heat than they receive from the Sun.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Models for the interiors of Jupiter and Saturn suggest that at a certain depth the hydrogen undergoes a phase change to a metallic hydrogen fluid mixed with ice.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] There is possibly a diffuse or solid core of more massive elements.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] For Uranus and Neptune, there is no metallic hydrogen; instead there are interior layers of ice, placing these worlds in the sub-category of ice giants.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] At sufficient depth, the ice may transition to a supercritical fluid.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Within the Solar System, gas giant planets formed beyond the frost line, where the temperature from the young Sun was low enough for volatiles to condense into solid grains.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] In some star systems, dynamic processes in the protoplanetary disk can cause a gas giant to migrate much closer to the central star, creating a hot Jupiter.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Through gravitational interaction, the orbit of the planet becomes circularized and it is tidally locked into a synchronous rotation with one side constantly facing the star.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The heated side becomes swollen, and high velocity winds distribute the thermal energy around the planet.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The atmosphere may eventually be stripped away by the star's gravity, leaving behind a super Earth.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] At the upper mass extreme of gas giants is a class of objects known as brown dwarfs.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] There is no universal consensus on how to distinguish a brown dwarf from a gas giant, although a commonly used criteria is the ability to fuse deuterium at around 13 times the mass of Jupiter.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Once the initial deuterium burning phase of a brown dwarf is concluded, the internal store of heat gradually makes its way to the surface then is radiated away over time.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Convection occurs around the core, and possibly at the surface if the brown dwarf is receiving energy from a nearby star.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Radiative energy transfer occurs throughout the remainder of the brown dwarf.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Chemistry can occur throughout the atmosphere, which, depending on the chemical species, can change the opacity to radiative energy transfer.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] As with gas giants, in the cooler outer regions of a brown dwarf, some molecules can condense to form clouds.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The circulation of the atmosphere occurs due to thermal differences when convection becomes a more efficient transporter of heat than thermal radiation.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] On planets where the primary heat source is solar radiation, excess heat in the tropics is transported to higher latitudes.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] When a planet generates a significant amount of heat internally, such as is the case for Jupiter, convection in the atmosphere can transport thermal energy from the higher temperature interior up to the surface.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The thermally-driven meridional circulation of Earth, Mars, and Venus are dominated by the Hadley cell.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] This is created by rising air in the warmest region of the planet accompanied by descending air where it is cooler.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] However, there are significant differences in the circulation patterns between the three planets.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] For Venus, the lower atmosphere of Venus has two symmetrical equator to near pole circulation cells, with a higher altitude sub-solar to anti-solar circulation cell.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] On Earth, Hadley cells exist on each side of the equator, but these vary seasonally due to the planet's obliquity.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Mars is similar to the Earth in this respect, but it displays greater seasonality due to its thinner atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] It has two Hadley cells during equinox, but a single cell at solstice.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The Earth has multiple counter-rotating convection cells, with the Hadley cell on either side of the equator, an intermediate Ferrel cell along the mid-latitudes, and polar cells at each pole.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The planet's rotation induces a Coriolis force that creates a curvature in the north-south convection flow.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] As air moves toward a pole, the latitudinal flow remains steady but the distance needed to encircle the planet grows shorter, creating a curved path along the surface.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] These flows create the prevailing winds along the planet's surface.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Near the equator, the air flow creates the trade winds which flow from east to west.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] At the mid-latitudes, the westerlies brings the air flow from the west in the United States and Europe.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Finally, the polar easterlies moves polar air from east to west.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Both Jupiter and Saturn display banded cloud formations.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] These are associated with alternating jets known as zonal flows that follow latitudinal lines.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The bands alternate in direction, with the equatorial jet moving eastward at 150 km/s on Jupiter and 300 km/s on Saturn.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] It remains unclear whether these flows occur in the shallow layers around the clouds, or extend much deeper into the atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Observations of Neptune show a similar zonal flow structure.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] This planet displays the largest range of differential rotation in the Solar System.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Surface gravity differs significantly among the planets.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] For example, the large gravitational force of the giant planet Jupiter retains light gases such as hydrogen and helium that escape from objects with lower gravity.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Secondly, the distance from the Sun determines the energy available to heat atmospheric gas to the point where some fraction of its molecules' thermal motion exceed the planet's escape velocity, allowing those to escape a planet's gravitational grasp.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Thus, distant and cold Titan, Triton, and Pluto are able to retain components of their original atmospheres despite their relatively low gravities.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Since a collection of gas molecules may be moving at a wide range of velocities, there will always be some fast enough to produce a slow leakage of gas into space.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Lighter molecules move faster than heavier ones with the same thermal kinetic energy, and so gases of low molecular weight are lost more rapidly than those of high molecular weight.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] It is thought that Venus and Mars may have lost much of their water when, after being photodissociated into hydrogen and oxygen by solar ultraviolet radiation, the hydrogen escaped.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Earth's magnetic field helps to prevent this, as, normally, the solar wind would greatly enhance the escape of hydrogen.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] However, over the past 3 billion years Earth may have lost gases through the magnetic polar regions due to auroral activity, including a net 2% of its atmospheric oxygen.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The net effect, taking the most important escape processes into account, is that an intrinsic magnetic field does not protect a planet from atmospheric escape and that for some magnetizations the presence of a magnetic field works to increase the escape rate.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Planets around small M-type main-sequence stars may be particularly prone to atmospheric loss.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The star will spend an extended period as a superluminous pre-main-sequence star, then experience high levels of activity.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The strong stellar magnetic field will tend to reduce the size of planetary magnetospheres, leading to greater erosion from the stellar wind.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Planets around older M-type stars may become tidally locked in synchronous orbit, leading to the atmosphere being permanently frozen on the dark face.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Other mechanisms that can cause atmosphere depletion are solar wind-induced sputtering, impact erosion, weathering, and sequestration—sometimes referred to as "freezing out"—into the regolith and polar caps.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] An extreme example of the latter is a comet, which is a small body that forms beyond the frost line in the protoplanetary disk.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] These objects contain many types of frozen volatiles, including water, carbon dioxide, ammonia, methane, and formaldehyde.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] As these objects approach the Sun, the thermal radiation causes the volatiles to sublimate, creating a diffuse, dusty atmosphere around the comet; the coma.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] However, the gravitational potential of the comet is insufficient to retain this atmosphere.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] The Solar System contains a large number of bodies that are now practically airless, such as Mercury and the Moon.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] These objects have only an exosphere layer with particles that are essentially collisionless.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] In this environment, atoms and molecules are released from the surface by various means, including particle sputtering and micrometeorite impact.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] When the release velocity of these particles exceed the escape velocity, they are lost to space.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Higher mass particles have a greater chance to be returned to the surface, which creates a chemical alteration of the surface over time.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] On a terrestrial planet, the part of the atmosphere that directly interacts with the ground is known as the planetary boundary layer.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Atmospheres have dramatic effects on the surfaces of rocky bodies.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Wind erosion is a significant factor in shaping the terrain of rocky planets with atmospheres, and over time can erase the effects of both craters and volcanoes.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] In addition, since liquids cannot exist without pressure, an atmosphere allows liquid to be present at the surface, resulting in lakes, rivers and oceans.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Earth and Titan are known to have liquids at their surface and terrain on the planet Mars suggests that it had liquid on its surface in the past.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Objects that have no atmosphere, or that have only an exosphere, have terrain that is covered in craters.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Without an atmosphere, the planet has no protection from meteoroids, and all of them collide with the surface as meteorites and create craters.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] For planets with a significant atmosphere, most meteoroids burn up as meteors before hitting a planet's surface.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] When meteoroids do impact, the effects are often erased by the action of wind.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] From the perspective of a planetary geologist, the atmosphere acts to shape a planetary surface.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Wind picks up dust and other particles which, when they collide with the terrain, erode the relief and leave deposits (eolian processes).
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Frost and precipitations, which depend on the atmospheric composition, also influence the relief.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Climate changes can influence a planet's geological history.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] Conversely, studying the surface of the Earth leads to an understanding of the atmosphere and climate of other planets.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] For a meteorologist, the composition of the Earth's atmosphere is a factor affecting the climate and its variations.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] For a biologist or paleontologist, the Earth's atmospheric composition is closely dependent on the appearance of life and its evolution.
[src:atmosphere/atmosphere] In astrobiology, the composition of an exoplanet's atmosphere is closely intertwined with the possibility of extraterrestrial life.
